(44, '.isdigit() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method &nbsp;<strong>.isdigit()</strong></p><p><strong>.isdigit()</strong> - Used to check whether the string contains only numerals.</p><p>When <strong>TRUE</strong> is returned that means only <strong>numerals</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>FALSE</strong> is returned that there are <strong>non-numeral characters</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isdigit()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isdigit()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage123123\"</p><p>print(str3.isdigit()) #using the method</p><p>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><p>#------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isdigit()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isdigit()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage123123\"</p><p>print(str3.isdigit()) #using the method</p><p>#------------------------</p>', '2'),
(45, '.islower() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method .islower()</p><p><strong>.islower()</strong> - Used to check whether the string is entirely in lower case.</p><p>When <strong>TRUE</strong> is returned that the string is entirely in <strong>lower case</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>FALSE</strong> is returned that the string is not entirely in <strong>lower case</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>&nbsp;str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>&nbsp;print(str1.islower()) #using the method</p><p>&nbsp;str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>&nbsp;print(str2.islower()) #using the method</p><p>&nbsp;str3 = \"i am learning python with glowworm academy\"</p><p>&nbsp;print(str3.islower()) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>&nbsp;str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>&nbsp;print(str1.islower()) #using the method</p><p>&nbsp;str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>&nbsp;print(str2.islower()) #using the method</p><p>&nbsp;str3 = \"i am learning python with glowworm academy\"</p><p>&nbsp;print(str3.islower()) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------</p>', '2'),
(46, '.isupper() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.isupper()</strong></p><p><strong>.isupper()</strong> - Used to check whether the string is entirely in upper case.</p><p>When <strong>TRUE</strong> is returned that the string is <strong>entirely in upper case</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>FALSE</strong> is returned that the string is <strong>not entirely in upper case</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isupper()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isupper()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isupper()) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><p>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isupper()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isupper()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isupper()) #using the method</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p>', '2'),
(47, '.isalnum() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.isalnum()</strong></p><p><strong>.isalnum()</strong> - Used to check if all the characters in the string <strong>are only alphanumeric</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>TRUE </strong>is returned that the string are <strong>only alphanumeric</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>FALSE </strong>is returned that the string <strong>not are only alphanumeric</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312Python123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isalnum()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"#%%$%^%@$$!@#%%\"</p><p>print(str4.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312Python123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isalnum()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"#%%$%^%@$$!@#%%\"</p><p>print(str4.isalnum()) #using the method</p><p>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(48, '.isspace() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.isspace()</strong></p><p><strong>.isspace()</strong> - Used to check if all the characters in the string are only whitespaces.</p><p>When <strong>TRUE</strong> is returned that the string are <strong>only whitespaces</strong>.</p><p>When <strong>FALSE</strong> is returned that the string <strong>not are only whitespaces</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute &nbsp;the code below:</strong></p><p>#----------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312Python123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isspace()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isspace()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isspace()) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \" &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"</p><p>print(str4.isspace()) #using the method</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312Python123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.isspace()) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.isspace()) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"I AM LEARNING PYTHON WITH GLOWWORM ACADEMY\"</p><p>print(str3.isspace()) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \" &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"</p><p>print(str4.isspace()) #using the method&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(49, '.split() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.split()</strong></p><p><strong>.split()</strong> - Used to split the entire string.</p><p>The split method is quite useful in and requires a little bit more attention.</p><p>This is specifically useful in case of&nbsp; <strong>Data Cleaning</strong>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>string.split(separator)</p></blockquote><p>The <strong>separator</strong> has to be supplied as a <strong>string</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------------------<br>str3 = \"I,am,learning,Python,with,Glowworm,Academy\"</p><p>print(str3.split(&#x27;,&#x27;))</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning Python with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.split(&#x27; &#x27;))</p><p>str5 = \"Bananannananananananana\" #Seperator is &#x27;n&#x27;</p><p>print(str5.split(&#x27;n&#x27;))</p><p>str5 = \"G1l1o1w1o1r1m1\"</p><p>print(str5.split(&#x27;1&#x27;))</p><p>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------------------<br>str3 = \"I,am,learning,Python,with,Glowworm,Academy\"</p><p>print(str3.split(&#x27;,&#x27;))</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning Python with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.split(&#x27; &#x27;))</p><p>str5 = \"Bananannananananananana\" #Seperator is &#x27;n&#x27;</p><p>print(str5.split(&#x27;n&#x27;))</p><p>str5 = \"G1l1o1w1o1r1m1\"</p><p>print(str5.split(&#x27;1&#x27;))</p><p>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(50, 'String Methods Exercises - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Store the following values in appropriate variables.<ul><li>First Name</li><li>Last Name</li><li>City</li><li>Zip code</li></ul></li><li>Display the first name in upper case</li><li>Display the last name in the lower case.</li><li>Replace the city with the city \"Ahmedabad\"</li><li>Add \"&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Python&nbsp; \" to the Zip code.</li><li>Print the stripped version of the Zip code.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><p>#Defining the variables</p><p>first_name = \"First Name\"</p><p>last_name = \"last Name\"</p><p>city_name = \"City Name\"</p><p>zip_code = \"380012\"</p><p>#Display the first name in upper case</p><p>print(first_name.upper())</p><p>#Display the last name in lower case</p><p>print(first_name.lower())</p><p>#Replace the city with the city \"Ahmedabad\"</p><p>print(city_name.replace(\"City Name\",\"Ahmedabad\"))</p><p>#Add \" &nbsp; &nbsp; Python &nbsp;\" to the Zip code.</p><p>zip_code = zip_code + \" &nbsp; &nbsp; Python &nbsp;\"</p><p>#Print the stripped version of the Zip code.</p><p>print(zip_code.strip())</p>', '2'),
(51, 'Strings Methods-III', 'Python', '<p>Some more popular string methods:</p><ol><li><strong>.rjust()</strong> - Returns the right justified version of the string.</li><li><strong>.ljust()</strong> - Returns the left justified version of the string.</li><li><strong>.center()</strong> - Returns the center justified version of the string.</li><li><strong>.startswith()</strong> - Returns True or False if the string starts with the specified text or not.<br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(52, '.rjust() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.rjust()</strong></p><p><strong>.rjust(justification)</strong> - Returns the right justified version of the string.</p><p>The <strong>justification</strong> has to be an integer that will move the text by the number of characters specified in the right direction.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.rjust(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.rjust(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.rjust(30)) #using the method<br>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.rjust(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.rjust(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.rjust(30)) #using the method<br>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(53, '.ljust() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.rjust()</strong></p><p><strong>.ljust(justification)</strong> - Returns the left justified version of the string.</p><p>The <strong>justification</strong> has to be an integer that will move the text by the number of characters specified in the left direction.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#----------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.ljust(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.ljust(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.ljust(30)) #using the method<br>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.ljust(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.ljust(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.ljust(30)) #using the method<br>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(54, '.center() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.center()</strong></p><p><strong>.center(justification)</strong> - Returns the center justified version of the string.</p><p>The <strong>justification</strong> has to be an integer that will move the text by the number of characters specified at both ends.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.center(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.center(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.center(30)) #using the method<br>#--------------------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#--------------------------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.center(20)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.center(10)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"Python@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.center(30)) #using the method<br>#--------------------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(55, '.startswith() method - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.center()</strong></p><p><strong>.startswith(text)</strong> - Returns True or False if the string starts with the specified text or not.</p><p>When <strong>True</strong> is returned that when the specified string starts with the specified text.<br>When <strong>False</strong> is returned that when the specified string does not start with the specified text.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.startswith(\"12\")) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.startswith(\"Pyth\")) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.startswith(\"@\")) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning programming with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.startswith(\"Glowworm\")) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.startswith(\"12\")) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.startswith(\"Pyth\")) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.startswith(\"@\")) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning programming with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.startswith(\"Glowworm\")) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(56, '.startswith() method - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try first method <strong>.center()</strong></p><p><strong>.startswith(text,start,end)</strong> - Returns True or False if the string starts with the specified text or not.</p><p>The <strong>.startswith</strong> method allows us to check not only the entire string but a <strong>part of string</strong> also.<br>Let&#x27;s call it a <strong>substring</strong>.</p><p><strong>start</strong> - starting index of the substring.</p><p><strong>end </strong>- ending index of the substring.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.startswith(\"12\",2,5)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.startswith(\"amaz\",13,20)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.startswith(\"@\",7,10)) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning programming with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.startswith(\"Glowworm\",31,40)) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>str1 = \"12312312123\" #Defining a numbers only string</p><p>print(str1.startswith(\"12\",2,5)) #using the method</p><p>str2 = \"Python is an amazing language\"</p><p>print(str2.startswith(\"amaz\",13,20)) #using the method<br><br>str3 = \"@!@#!@%^#!$@$Clanguage\"</p><p>print(str3.startswith(\"@\",7,10)) #using the method</p><p>str4 = \"I am learning programming with Glowworm Academy\"</p><p>print(str4.startswith(\"Glowworm\",31,40)) #using the method</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(57, 'String Methods Exercises - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your learning.</p><p>Write a code to execute the following.</p><p>#Task1</p><ol><li>Define a variable &lt;b&gt;password&lt;/b&gt; with a value (combination of letters, special characters and numbers) of your choice.</li><li>Define a variable email ID &lt;b&gt;email&lt;/b&gt; with your email ID.</li></ol><p>#Task2</p><ol><li>Check whether the password has only numbers and alphabets or not?</li><li>Find the &#x27;@&#x27; index in the email ID?</li><li>Split the email ID at @ and extract the domain name.<br>&nbsp;</li></ol><p>For example, &lt;b&gt;data@glowedu.co.in&lt;/b&gt; should become, &lt;b&gt;[&#x27;data&#x27;,&#x27;glowedu.co.in&#x27;]&lt;/b&gt;<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining variables</p><p>password = \"mypassword@1234\"</p><p>email = \"Testemail@dummy.com\"</p><p>#Checking whether the password has only numbers and alphabets or not</p><p>print(\"Does the password contain only numbers and alphabets: \")</p><p>print(password.isalnum())</p><p>#Find the &#x27;@&#x27; index in the email ID</p><p>print(\"The index of ‘@’ in email is: \")&nbsp;</p><p>print(email.find(\"@\"))</p><p>#Split the email ID at @ and extract the domain name.</p><p>print(\"The domain name of the entered email is: \")&nbsp;</p><p>print(email.split(\"@\"))</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(58, 'List', 'Python', '<p>Python list object is the most general sequence provided by the language.</p><p>Lists are positionally ordered collections of arbitrarily typed objects without any fixed size.</p><p>They are also mutable and are quite flexible in terms of storage.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; list_name = [element1,element2,...]</p><p>Lists are always defined with the &lt;b&gt;square brackets []&lt;/b&gt; and the elements are separated by &lt;b&gt;comma (,)&lt;/b&gt;.&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(59, 'List Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some of the basic operations of the list.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list&nbsp;<br>lst1 = [123, &#x27;spam&#x27;, 1.23]</p><p>print(lst1)</p><p>#---------------------<br>lst2 = [&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python is Easy&#x27; , 2014]</p><p>print(lst2)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Another way of defining list using keyword &#x27;list()&#x27;<br>lst3 &nbsp;= list([1,2,35,6,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;])</p><p>print(lst3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Joining two lists<br>lst4 = lst1 + lst2 + lst3</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetion of elements<br>lst4 = lst1*4</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty list<br>lst_empty = []</p><p>print(lst_empty)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#converting a string into a list<br>str1 = &#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;</p><p>lst = list(str1)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list&nbsp;<br>lst1 = [123, &#x27;spam&#x27;, 1.23]</p><p>print(lst1)</p><p>#---------------------<br>lst2 = [&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python is Easy&#x27; , 2014]</p><p>print(lst2)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Another way of defining list using keyword &#x27;list()&#x27;<br>lst3 &nbsp;= list([1,2,35,6,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;])</p><p>print(lst3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Joining two lists<br>lst4 = lst1 + lst2 + lst3</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetion of elements<br>lst4 = lst1*4</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty list<br>lst_empty = []</p><p>print(lst_empty)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#converting a string into a list<br>str1 = &#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;</p><p>lst = list(str1)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(60, 'List Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some of the basic operations of the list.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [12,3,123,12,90]</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sum of the list<br>print(sum(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the maximum value of the list<br>print(max(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the minimum value of the list<br>print(min(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = &#x27;sadasdasdgqqwd&#x27;</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [12,3,123,12,90]</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sum of the list<br>print(sum(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the maximum value of the list<br>print(max(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the minimum value of the list<br>print(min(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = &#x27;sadasdasdgqqwd&#x27;</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(61, 'List Operations - III', 'Python', '<p>Many times in a long list we may be interested to check if there are any &lt;b&gt;empty elements&lt;/b&gt; in the list.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i>Keyword</i></th><th><i>Application</i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>any</td><td>It will return True when there is at least one empty element in the list</td></tr><tr><td>all</td><td>It will return True when there are all empty elements in the list</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[],[]]</p><p>#any keyword<br>print(any(lst))<br>#--------------------<br>lst = []</p><p>#all keyword<br>print(all(lst))<br>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#--------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[],[]]</p><p>#any keyword<br>print(any(lst))<br>#--------------------<br>lst = []</p><p>#all keyword<br>print(all(lst))<br>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(62, 'List Slicing - I', 'Python', '<p>We store data to use it at a later point in time.</p><p>Let&#x27;s focus on how we can use list slicing to extract the store data.</p><p><strong>Always remember that Python starts indexing with 0.</strong></p><p>Create a <strong>5 element</strong> list of your choice name it to <strong>&#x27;lst&#x27;</strong></p><p>Then, copy the following code and run it.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#----------------------------</p><p>print(\"The the 0th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 1st element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 2nd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 3rd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the4th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the list<br>#----------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------------</p><p>print(\"The the 0th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 1st element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 2nd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 3rd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the4th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the list<br>#----------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(63, 'List Slicing - II', 'Python', '<p>We may not always want single elements but may need to a &lt;b&gt;print&lt;/b&gt; a bunch of elements.<br>Then our syntax slightly changes.</p><p>Create a &lt;b&gt;10 element&lt;/b&gt; list of your choice name it &lt;b&gt;&#x27;lst&#x27;&lt;/b&gt;, then copy the code below:</p><p>We use &lt;b&gt;:&lt;/b&gt; to specify a range.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>Always remember that the number after the column is ignored.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Execute the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#----------------------------</p><p>print(lst[2:7]) #Prints the 3rd to 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(lst[:7]) #Prints all the elements till 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(lst[3:]) #Prints all the elements from 3rd to the end of the list</p><p>#----------------------------</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Show Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------------</p><p>print(lst[2:7]) #Prints the 3rd to 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(lst[:7]) #Prints all the elements till 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(lst[3:]) #Prints all the elements from 3rd to the end of the list</p><p>#----------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(64, 'List Slicing - III', 'Python', '<p>So far we have used only positive numbers in for displaying the elements in the list .</p><p>Python also has something called the &lt;b&gt;Negative Indexing&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>Create a &lt;b&gt;10 element&lt;/b&gt; list of your choice name it &lt;b&gt;&#x27;lst&#x27;&lt;/b&gt;, then copy the code below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;</p><p>Always remember that the number after the column is ignored.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#-------------------------</p><p>print(lst[-1])<br>#Prints the last element</p><p>print(lst[-5]) &nbsp;<br>#Prints the 6th element from the backwards</p><p>print(lst[-5:-3])&nbsp;<br>#Prints the 3rd to 5th element from the backwards</p><p>print(lst[-5:])<br>#Prints all the elements to 5th element from the backwards including the 5th</p><p>print(lst[:-3])<br>#Prints all the elements from 3rd element till the very first element excluding the 3rd element<br>#-------------------------</p>', 'White (normal card)', '', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Show Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------</p><p>print(lst[-1])<br>#Prints the last element</p><p>print(lst[-5]) &nbsp;<br>#Prints the 6th element from the backwards</p><p>print(lst[-5:-3])&nbsp;<br>#Prints the 3rd to 5th element from the backwards</p><p>print(lst[-5:])<br>#Prints all the elements to 5th element from the backwards including the 5th</p><p>print(lst[:-3])<br>#Prints all the elements from 3rd element till the very first element excluding the 3rd element<br>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(65, 'List Slicing - IV', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s talk about &lt;b&gt;out-of-bounds&lt;/b&gt; error.</p><p>As we learnt previously, lists store data in an order.</p><p>So what if we try to request to print an element which is<br>not there in the list.</p><p>We get something called as &lt;b&gt;out-of-bounds&lt;/b&gt; error.</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#-------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;Apple&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the 7th element in the list<br>print(lst[7])</p><p>#Do observe the error.<br>#Since we only have six elements we can&#x27;t Python to print the 7th element.</p><p>#-------------------------</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Show Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;Apple&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the 7th element in the list<br>print(lst[7])</p><p>#Do observe the error.<br>#Since we only have six elements we can&#x27;t Python to print the 7th element.</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(66, 'List Exercise - I', 'Python', '<p>Create a list of 15 elements named as <strong>lst</strong> using user input print the all the elements at even index positions.</p><p>Use <strong>positive indexing</strong> method.</p><p>Always remember, python <strong>starts indexing with 0.</strong></p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Printing all even indexed elements.</p><p>print(lst[0])</p><p>print(lst[2])</p><p>print(lst[4])</p><p>print(lst[6])</p><p>print(lst[8])</p><p>print(lst[10])</p><p>print(lst[12])</p><p>print(lst[14])</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(67, 'List Exercise-II', 'Python', '<p>Create a list of 15 elements named as &lt;b&gt;lst&lt;/b&gt; using user input print the all the elements at odd index positions.</p><p>Use positive indexing method.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Printing all odd indexed elements.</p><p>print(lst[1])</p><p>print(lst[3])</p><p>print(lst[5])</p><p>print(lst[7])</p><p>print(lst[9])</p><p>print(lst[11])</p><p>print(lst[13])</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(68, 'List Exercise - III', 'Python', '<p>Create a list of 15 elements named &lt;b&gt;lst&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>Print the all the elements at even positions using negative indexing.</p><p>Use negative indexing method.</p><p>Don&#x27;t leave an enter between two lines of code.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Printing all odd indexed elements using negative indexing.</p><p>print(lst[-1])</p><p>print(lst[-3])</p><p>print(lst[-5])</p><p>print(lst[-7])</p><p>print(lst[-9])</p><p>print(lst[-11])</p><p>print(lst[-13])</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(69, 'List Methods - I', 'Python', '<p>Similar to string we have a bunch of methods that comes handy to all the coders.</p><p>For a list defined as &lt;b&gt;lst&lt;/b&gt; the syntax will be as below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;</p><p>lst.method()</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some popular methods:</p><ol><li><strong>.append()</strong> - Adds an element to the end of an list.</li><li><strong>.clear()</strong> - Clears all the elements from a list</li><li><strong>.copy()</strong> - Creating a copy of the list</li><li>.<strong>count()</strong> - Counting the number of elements in a list</li><li><strong>.extend()</strong> - Adding objects (not necessarily list) to the list</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(70, 'List Methods - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s see some examples on this list methods.</p><blockquote><p>&lt;b&gt;Execute the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#-------------------------</p><p>lst = [1,2,3,4, &#x27;list methods&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;]</p><p>lst1 = [&#x27;r&#x27;,&#x27;t&#x27;,&#x27;s&#x27;,&#x27;w&#x27;,&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]<br>#Append method</p><p>lst.append(5) #Appneding 5 to the list</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#Clearing the list through clear method<br>lst1.clear()</p><p>lst1</p><p>#Creating a copy of the list<br>lst3 = lst.copy()</p><p>lst3</p><p>#Counting the number a particular element appear in &nbsp;the list<br>print(lst.count(&#x27;Python&#x27;))</p><p>#Extending the list by adding another list</p><p>lst.extend(lst3)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', ' Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------</p><p>lst = [1,2,3,4, &#x27;list methods&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;]</p><p>lst1 = [&#x27;r&#x27;,&#x27;t&#x27;,&#x27;s&#x27;,&#x27;w&#x27;,&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]<br>#Append method</p><p>lst.append(5) #Appneding 5 to the list</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#Clearing the list through clear method<br>lst1.clear()</p><p>lst1</p><p>#Creating a copy of the list<br>lst3 = lst.copy()</p><p>lst3</p><p>#Counting the number a particular element appear in &nbsp;the list<br>print(lst.count(&#x27;Python&#x27;))</p><p>#Extending the list by adding another list</p><p>lst.extend(lst3)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(71, 'List Methods Exercises - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Define a list named as &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;lst.&lt;/b&gt;</li><li>Add &#x27;Python&#x27; to the list.</li><li>Clear the list.</li><li>Define a new list named as &lt;b&gt;lst2.&lt;/b&gt;</li><li>Create a copy of that list and store it into &lt;b&gt;new_lst.&lt;/b&gt;</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining the first list</p><p>lst = [1,2,3,4]</p><p>print(\"The original list is\",lst)</p><p>#Add &#x27;Python&#x27; to the list.</p><p>lst.append(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is : \",lst)</p><p>#Clear the list.</p><p>lst.clear()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is : \",lst)</p><p>#Defining the second list</p><p>lst2 = [11,22,33,44]</p><p>print(\"The second list is: \",lst2)</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(72, 'List Methods Exercises - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Define lists named as &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;lst1.&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;lst2.&lt;/b&gt;</li><li>Join them to make another list named as &lt;b&gt;lst3&lt;/b&gt;</li><li>Extend the list &lt;b&gt;lst3&lt;/b&gt; by [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;]</li><li>Print the count of element &#x27;Python&#x27; in the list lst3.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining lists</p><p>lst1 = [1,2,3,4]</p><p>lst2 = [5,6,7,8]</p><p>#Joining two lists</p><p>lst3 = lst1 + lst2</p><p>print(\"The new list is: \",lst3)</p><p>#Extending the list</p><p>lst3.extend([&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;])</p><p>print(\"The updated list lst3 is: \",lst3)</p><p>#Print the count of element &#x27;Python&#x27; in the list lst3.</p><p>print(\"The count of Python in lst3 is: \",lst3.count(&#x27;Python&#x27;))</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(73, 'List Methods-III', 'Python', '<p>Some more useful list methods.</p><ol><li><strong>.insert()</strong> - Adding an element to the list at a position of users choice.</li><li><strong>.index()</strong> - Returns the index of the first element with the specified value.</li><li><strong>.pop()</strong> - Removes the element at a location of users choice.</li><li><strong>.remove() </strong>- Removes the first item with the specified value.</li><li><strong>.reverse()</strong> - Reverses the list.</li><li><strong>.sort()</strong> -Sorts the list.<br>&nbsp;</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(74, '.insert() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.insert()</strong></p><p><strong>.insert()</strong> - Adding an element to the list at a position of users choice.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>lst.insert(index,element)</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Orange&#x27;]</p><p>#Defining a list lst1<br>lst1 = [&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Javascript&#x27;,&#x27;C Language&#x27;]&nbsp;<br><br>#Inserting a list to another list at index 2<br>lst.insert(2,lst1)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Inserting a list to another list at index -1<br>lst.insert(-1,lst1)<br><br>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Inserting a list to another list at index 3<br>lst.insert(3,&#x27;test element&#x27;)<br><br>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Inserting an element from another to another list at index 3<br>lst.insert(-1,lst1[2])<br><br>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Orange&#x27;]</p><p>#Defining a list lst1<br>lst1 = [&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Javascript&#x27;,&#x27;C Language&#x27;]</p><p>#Inserting a list to another list at index 2<br>lst.insert(2,lst1)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p><br>#Inserting a list to another list at index -1<br>lst.insert(-1,lst1)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Inserting a list to another list at index 3<br>lst.insert(3,&#x27;test element&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Inserting an element from another to another list at index 3<br>lst.insert(-1,lst1[2])</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(75, '.index() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.index()</strong></p><p><strong>.index()</strong> - Returns the index of the first element with the specified value.</p><p><strong>Syntax:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>lst.index(element)</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Finding the index first time occurrence of an element<br>lst.index(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Finding the index first time occurrence of a list<br>lst.index(&#x27;Apple&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Finding the index first time occurrence of an element<br>lst.index(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Finding the index first time occurrence of a list<br>lst.index(&#x27;Apple&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(76, '.pop() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.pop()</strong></p><p><strong>.pop()</strong> - Removes the element at a location of users choice.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>lst.pop(index)</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Removing an element at the index 3<br>lst.pop(3)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Removing an element at the index 7<br>lst.pop(7)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)<br>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><i><strong>Sample Code:</strong></i></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]</p><p>#Removing an element at the index 3<br>lst.pop(3)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Removing an element at the index 7<br>lst.pop(7)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)<br>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(77, '.remove() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.remove()</strong></p><p><strong>.remove()</strong> - Removes the first item with the specified value.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>lst.remove(element)</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#----------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Removing an element at the index 3<br>lst.remove(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Removing an element at the index 7<br>lst.remove([&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;])</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)<br>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Removing an element at the index 3<br>lst.remove(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Removing an element at the index 7<br>lst.remove([&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;])</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)<br>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(78, '.reverse() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.reverse()</strong></p><p><strong>.reverse()</strong> - Reverses the list.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>lst.reverse()</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.reverse()</p><p>lst</p><p>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><i><strong>Sample Code:</strong></i></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#------------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.reverse()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2');
