(79, '.sort() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.sort()</strong></p><p><strong>.sort()</strong> - sort the list.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>lst.sort()</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#----------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an ascending order<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [&#x27;z&#x27;,&#x27;t&#x27;,&#x27;e&#x27;,&#x27;d&#x27;]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;,&#x27;d&#x27;]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------<br>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an ascending order<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [1,2,3,4]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [&#x27;z&#x27;,&#x27;t&#x27;,&#x27;e&#x27;,&#x27;d&#x27;]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;,&#x27;d&#x27;]</p><p>#Sorting a list in an descending order<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#Defining a list lst<br>lst = [4,3,2,1,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, [&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;], &nbsp;&#x27;Orange&#x27;]<br><br>#Reversing the list<br>lst.sort(reverse = False)</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: \",lst)</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(80, 'List Methods Exercises - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your learning.</p><p>Write a code to execute the following.</p><ol><li>Define a list named<strong> lst</strong> comprising only of letters.</li><li>Store your first name in lower case in <strong>first_name</strong> .</li><li>Store your&nbsp;phone number in <strong>phone_number</strong>.</li><li>Store your password with only numbers and letters in<strong> password</strong>.</li><li>Store your email ID in email.</li><li>Print the sorted version of lst.</li><li>Convert the first_name into a list and remove the last letter.</li><li>Convert the phone_number into a list and sort.</li><li>Convert the password into a list and remove last 3 characters.</li><li>Split the email into a list and replace the domain name with &#x27;Python.com&#x27;</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining a list</p><p>lst = [&#x27;t&#x27;,&#x27;y&#x27;,&#x27;u&#x27;,&#x27;r&#x27;,&#x27;e&#x27;,&#x27;g&#x27;]</p><p>#Defining the first_name</p><p>first_name = \"First Name\"</p><p>#Defining the phone_number</p><p>phone_number = \"12345678910\"</p><p>#Defining the password</p><p>password = \"MyPassword1234\"</p><p>#Defining the email</p><p>email = \"myemailid@gmaill.com\"</p><p>#Sorted list</p><p>lst = lst.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list is: ,\",lst)</p><p>#Convert the first_name into a list and remove the last letter.</p><p>first_name = list(first_name)</p><p>first_name.pop(-1)</p><p>print(\"The updated list of the first name is: \",first_name)</p><p>#Convert the phone_number into a list and sort.</p><p>phone_number = list(phone_number)</p><p>phone_number.sort()</p><p>print(\"The updated list of the first name is: \",phone_number)</p><p>#Convert the password into a list and sort.</p><p>password = list(password)</p><p>password.pop(-1)</p><p>password.pop(-1)</p><p>password.pop(-1)</p><p>print(\"The updated list of the password is: \",password)</p><p>#Split the email into a list and replace the domain name with &#x27;Python.com&#x27;</p><p>email = list(email)</p><p>email.pop(-1)</p><p>email.append(&#x27;Python.com&#x27;)</p><p>print(\"The updated list of the email ID is: \",email)</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(81, 'List Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Basically, the nesting of list is putting a list within a list.</p><p>That allows the user to store the data in a multi-layer basis.</p><p><strong>Syntax</strong>:</p><p>list_name[index][index]...[index]</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong><br>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample code:</strong></h4><p>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(82, 'List Nesting - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try something more complex.</p><p><strong>Syntax</strong>:</p><p>list_name[index][index]...[index]</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong><br>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,[&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list[&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2][1])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,[&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list[&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2][1])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(83, 'List Nesting Exercise', 'Python', '<p>Now, let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Let&#x27;s imagine you have a list as below:</p><p>lst = [1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,[123123,1456,[546$21,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,[&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,[&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;]]],21321]]</p><p><br>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Define the above list.</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Orange&#x27;.</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Chicago&#x27;.</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Python&#x27;</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining the list</p><p>lst = [1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,[123123,1456,[546$21,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,[&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,[&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;]]],21321]]</p><p>#Printing the Orange</p><p>print(lst[4][2][2])</p><p>#Printing the Chicago</p><p>print(lst[4][2][3][2])</p><p>#Printing the Python</p><p>print(lst[4][2][3][4][2])</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(84, 'Dictionary', 'Python', '<p>Python dictionaries are something completely different.&nbsp;</p><p>They are not sequences at all, but are instead known as <strong>mappings</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Mappings</strong> are also collections of other objects. Some important points:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>They store objects by key instead of by relative position.&nbsp;</li><li>They don&#x27;t store the data in any particular order.&nbsp;</li><li>Dictionaries are mutable.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(85, 'Dictionary Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first dictionary and look at some basic operations.&nbsp;</p><p>This method is handy if you can spell out the entire dictionary ahead of time.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>dictionary_name = {&#x27;key1&#x27;:value1,&#x27;key2&#x27;:value2....}&nbsp;</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary of fruits&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the original dictionary</p><p>print(\"The original dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#Retrieving data from dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1[&#x27;fruit1&#x27;])&nbsp;</p><p>#Displaying the length of dictionary print(len(d1))&nbsp;</p><p>#Modifying a value in the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;fruit5&#x27;] = &#x27;Mango&#x27; print(d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Checking whether a particular element belongs to the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(&#x27;Apple&#x27; in d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Removing a particular element from the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>del d1[&#x27;fruit3&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the updated dictionary</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary of fruits&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the original dictionary</p><p>print(\"The original dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#Retrieving data from dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1[&#x27;fruit1&#x27;])&nbsp;</p><p>#Displaying the length of dictionary print(len(d1))&nbsp;</p><p>#Modifying a value in the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;fruit5&#x27;] = &#x27;Mango&#x27; print(d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Checking whether a particular element belongs to the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(&#x27;Apple&#x27; in d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Removing a particular element from the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>del d1[&#x27;fruit3&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the updated dictionary</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(86, 'Dictionary Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at a different way of defining a dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p>This is useful when you need to create the dictionary one field at a time.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty dictionary</p><p>d1 = {}</p><p>#Adding one element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;New York&#x27;</p><p>#Adding second element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City2&#x27;] = &#x27;Zurich&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding third element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City3&#x27;] = &#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding fourth element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;London&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \",d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty dictionary</p><p>d1 = {}</p><p>#Adding one element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;New York&#x27;</p><p>#Adding second element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City2&#x27;] = &#x27;Zurich&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding third element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City3&#x27;] = &#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding fourth element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;London&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \",d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(87, 'Dictionary Operations - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some other ways of defining a dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p>The first method below, involves less typing, but it requires all keys to be strings.&nbsp;</p><p>The second method below, is useful if you need to build up keys and values as sequences at runtime.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Using the keyword &#x27;dict()&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict(name=&#x27;Bob&#x27;, age=40,city = Baden, profession = &#x27;Engineer&#x27;)&nbsp;</p><p>#dict key/value tuples form&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict([(&#x27;name&#x27;,&#x27;Bob&#x27;), (&#x27;age&#x27;,40),(&#x27;city&#x27;,&#x27;Baden&#x27;), (&#x27;profession&#x27;,&#x27;Engineer&#x27;)])</p><p>&nbsp;#More on the tuples later</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong>&nbsp;</h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Using the keyword &#x27;dict()&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict(name=&#x27;Bob&#x27;, age=40,city = Baden, profession = &#x27;Engineer&#x27;)&nbsp;</p><p>#dict key/value tuples form&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict([(&#x27;name&#x27;,&#x27;Bob&#x27;), (&#x27;age&#x27;,40),(&#x27;city&#x27;,&#x27;Baden&#x27;), (&#x27;profession&#x27;,&#x27;Engineer&#x27;)])</p><p>&nbsp;#More on the tuples later</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(88, 'Dictionary Methods - I', 'Python', '<p>Just like strings, list and other objects dictionary contains a number of useful methods that is useful for any programmer.&nbsp;</p><p>For a list defined as D the syntax will be as below:</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>D.method()&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Following are some of the dictionary methods</strong></p><ol><li><strong>.keys()</strong> - Displaying all the keys of the dictionary.</li><li><strong>.values()</strong> - Displaying all the keys of the dictionary.</li><li><strong>.items()</strong> - Displaying all the keys and values of the dictionary.</li><li><strong>.copy()</strong> - Creates a copy of the dictionary.</li><li><strong>.clear()</strong> - Removing all the elements of the dictionary.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(89, '.keys() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method<strong> .keys()</strong></p><p><strong>.keys() </strong>- Displaying all the keys of the dictionary.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong> D.keys()</p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>Observe that the output of this method is a new built-in Python object called &#x27;dict_keys&#x27;.</p><p>This can be converted into a list, set, tuple etc. which can be then used for further.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The keys of the dictionary is: \",d1.keys())</p><p>print(\"The data type of keys of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.keys))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(90, '.values() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.values()</strong></p><p><strong>.values() </strong>- Displaying all the values of the dictionary.</p><p><strong>Syntax:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>D.values()</p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>Observe that the output of this method is a new built-in Python object called &#x27;dict_values&#x27;.</p><p>This can be converted into a list, set, tuple etc. which can be then used for further.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The values of the dictionary is: \",d1.values())</p><p>print(\"The data type values of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.values))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(91, '.items() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.items()</strong></p><p><strong>.items()</strong> - Displaying all the keys and values of the dictionary.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>D.items()</p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>Observe that the output of this method is a new built-in Python object called &#x27;dict_items&#x27;.</p><p>This can be converted into a list, set, tuple etc. which can be then used for further.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:[10,20,30,40,50],3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing all the keys and values of the dictionary</p><p>print(\"All the keys and values of the dictionary is : \",d1.items())</p><p>print(\"The data type of items of the dictionary is: \",type(d1.items))</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(92, '.clear() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method <strong>.clear() &nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>.clear()</strong> - Removing all the elements of the dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Syntax :</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>D.clear()&nbsp;</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the cleared dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1.clear())&nbsp;</p><p>#Updating the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = d1.clear()&nbsp;</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the cleared dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1.clear())&nbsp;</p><p>#Updating the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = d1.clear()&nbsp;</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(93, '.copy() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s the method .copy() &nbsp;</p><p>.copy() - Creates a copy of the dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p>Syntax :&nbsp;</p><p>D.copy()&nbsp;</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the copied dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1.copy())&nbsp;</p><p>#Updating the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = d1.copy()&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the copied dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1.copy())&nbsp;</p><p>#Updating the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = d1.copy()&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '2'),
(94, 'Dictionary Methods - II', 'Python', '<p>Some more dictionary methods.&nbsp;</p><p>For a list defined as D the syntax will be as below:&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Syntax:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>D.method()</p><p><strong>Following are some of the dictionary methods</strong></p><ol><li><strong>.update()</strong> - Inserts the desired element to an existing dictionary.</li><li><strong>.get()</strong> - Fetching the element using the key.</li><li><strong>.pop()</strong> - Removing the element using the key.</li><li><strong>.setdefault()</strong> - Sets a default value for the key specified.</li><li><strong>.popitem()</strong> - Removes the item that was last inserted into the dictionary.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(95, '.update() method', 'Python', 'Let&#x27;s the method  .keys()      .update()  - Inserts the desired element to an existing dictionary.    Syntax: D.update({key:value})     Copy the code below:   #--------------------------------------    #Defining a dictionary  d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}    #Updating a dictionary  d1.update({&#x27;fruit6&#x27;:&#x27;Mango&#x27;})    print(d1)    #Updating a dictionary with multiple elements  d1.update({&#x27;fruit6&#x27;:&#x27;Mango&#x27;,&#x27;fruit7&#x27;:&#x27;Tomato&#x27;})    print(d1)    #Updating a dictionary with a list  lst = [&#x27;Tomato&#x27;, &#x27;Peas&#x27;, &#x27;Eggplant&#x27;]    d1.update({&#x27;vegetables&#x27;:lst})    print(d1)    #Updating a dictionary with a dictionary  d2 = {&#x27;city1&#x27;:&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;city2&#x27;:&#x27;Baden&#x27;}    d1.update({&#x27;city&#x27;:d2})    print(d1)    #Updating a dictionary   d1.update({&#x27;element&#x27;:d1[&#x27;fruit4&#x27;]})    print(d1)', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the reveal answer and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(96, '.get() method', 'Python', 'Let&#x27;s the method  .get()      .get()  - Fetching  the element using the key.    This is good only for extracting one element at a time.    We need to use a smarter method (discussed later) to make it   work for multiple elements.    Syntax: D.get(key)     Copy the code below:   #--------------------------------------    #Defining a dictionary    d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}    #Printing values based using the key  print(d1.get(&#x27;fruit1&#x27;))    #Defining a dictionary  d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}    #Printing values based using the key  print(d1.get(3))  ', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the reveal answer and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(97, '.pop() method', 'Python', 'Let&#x27;s the method  .pop()      .pop()  - Removing  the element using the key.    Syntax: D.pop(key)     Copy the code below:   #--------------------------------------    #Defining a dictionary  d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}    #Removing an element   d1.pop(&#x27;fruit4&#x27;)    print(d1)    #Defining a dictionary  d1 = {1:&#x27;Student1&#x27;,2:&#x27;Student2&#x27;,3:&#x27;Student3&#x27;,4:&#x27;Student4&#x27;,5:&#x27;Student5&#x27;}    #Removing an element   d1.pop(1)    print(d1)  ', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the reveal answer and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(98, 'Key Error', 'Python', '<p>Previously, we have only tried to print values that were from our dictionary.</p><p>What if we supply a key which is not there in the dictionary?</p><p>We will get something called as the <strong>&#x27;key error&#x27;</strong></p><p>This will stop the program execution.</p><p>Let&#x27;s go through an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Supplying a key which is not there in the dictionary</p><p>#Observe the output</p><p>print(d1[&#x27;fruit8&#x27;])</p><p>#This statement will not be executed</p><p>print(\\\"I have overcome the key error in the dictionary\\\")</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(99, '.setdefault() method - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;.setdefault()&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.setdefault()&lt;/b&gt; - Sets a default value for the key specified.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax&lt;/b&gt;: D.setdefault(key,value)</p><p>This method allows us to fix a default value for&nbsp;<br>a particular key of the users choice.</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><p>If the supplied key is absent in the dictionary,<br>it will add that to the dictionary.</p><p>It also allows the execution of rest of the program statements.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#-------------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>d1.setdefault(&#x27;fruit6&#x27;,&#x27;Strawberry&#x27;)</p><p>d1[&#x27;fruit6&#x27;]</p><p>print(\\\"I have overcome the key error in the dictionary\\\")</p><p>#-------------------------</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(100, '.setdefault() method - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s revisit the method &lt;b&gt;.get&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;.pop&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>The function and the syntax remains same.</p><p>But, let&#x27;s explore an additional functionality.</p><p>As the &lt;b&gt;.setdefault()&lt;/b&gt; method it allows us to avoid the key error&nbsp;<br>and continue with the program execution.</p><p>However, it doesn&#x27;t change the dictionary.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Updating a dictionary<br>print(d1.get(&#x27;fruit9&#x27;,&#x27;This is the default message for the get method&#x27;))</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#Updating a dictionary<br>print(d1.pop(&#x27;fruit9&#x27;,&#x27;This is the default message for the pop method&#x27;))</p><p>print(d1)<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(101, '.popitem() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;.popitem()&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.popitem()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes the item that was last inserted into the dictionary.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax&lt;/b&gt;: D.popitem()</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Updating a dictionary<br>d1.update({&#x27;fruit6&#x27;:&#x27;Mango&#x27;})</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#Removing the last item from the dictionary<br>d1.popitem()</p><p>print(d1)<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(102, 'Dictionary Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Just like the list nesting there &lt;b&gt;the dictionary&lt;/b&gt; offers<br>the nesting functionality.</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>print(nested_dict)</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(103, 'Dictionary Nesting - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at how to retrieve the stored data.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; dictionary_name[&#x27;key1&#x27;][&#x27;key2&#x27;]</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>#Printing the nested dictionary<br>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#Extracting an element of the dicitonary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict1&#x27;][&#x27;city&#x27;])</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(104, 'Dictionary Nesting - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at how to retrieve the stored data.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;lst3&#x27; : [5,6,7,8], &#x27;lst4&#x27;: [&#x27;d&#x27;,&#x27;e&#x27;,&#x27;f&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d3 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;,{&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1}],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;,{&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict={&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2,&#x27;dict3&#x27;:d3}</p><p>#Printing a nested dictionary<br>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#Extracting an element from the dictionary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict3&#x27;][&#x27;city&#x27;][3])</p><p>#Extracting an element from the dictionary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict3&#x27;][&#x27;Seasons&#x27;][3])<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(105, 'Dictionary Nesting - IV', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at how to retrieve the stored data.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;lst3&#x27; : [5,6,7,8], &#x27;lst4&#x27;: [&#x27;d&#x27;,&#x27;e&#x27;,&#x27;f&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:{&#x27;dict2&#x27;:{&#x27;dict3&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict4&#x27;:d2}}}</p><p>#Printing a nested dictionary<br>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#Extracting an element from the dictionary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict1&#x27;][&#x27;dict2&#x27;][&#x27;dict4&#x27;])</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(106, 'Dictionary Exercises - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does he following:</p><p>1. Create a list of first 10 even numbers named as &lt;b&gt;lst1&lt;/b&gt;.<br>2. Create a list of first 10 odd numbers named as &lt;b&gt;lst2&lt;/b&gt;.<br>3. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;keys&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;Even&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and &lt;b&gt;Odd&lt;/b&gt;.<br>4. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;lst1&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and &lt;b&gt;lst2&lt;/b&gt;.<br>5. Print the odd numbers list using the dictionary key.<br>Print the even numbers list using the dictionary key.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(107, 'Dictionary Exercises - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does he following:</p><p>1. Create a list of 3 fruit names named as <strong>lst1</strong> containing <strong>Orange, Apple and Mango</strong>.<br>2. Create a list of 3 vegetables names &nbsp;named as <strong>lst2</strong> containing <strong>Tomato, Cucumber and Onion</strong>.<br>3. Define a dictionary <strong>d1</strong> using <strong>keys</strong> as <strong>Fruit</strong>.<br>4. Define a dictionary <strong>d1</strong> using <strong>values</strong> as <strong>lst1</strong> .<br>5. Update the dictionary d1 using by adding the <strong>key</strong> as <strong>vegetables</strong> and <strong>values</strong> as <strong>lst2</strong>.&nbsp;<br>6. Print the updated dictionary.<br>7. Print the Tomato using the dictionary get method.<br>8. Remove the Onion from the dictionary using the pop method.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(108, 'Dictionary Exercises - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>You are going to create a employee database using the learnings<br>of list and dictionary.</p><p>Write a code that does he following:</p><p>1. Create a list of employee names named as &lt;b&gt;lst1.&lt;/b&gt;<br>2. Create a list of employee city named as &lt;b&gt;lst2.&lt;/b&gt;<br>3. Create a list of employee designation named as &lt;b&gt;lst3.&lt;/b&gt;<br>4. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;keys&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;Employee Names&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and &lt;b&gt;Employee City&lt;/b&gt;.<br>5. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;lst1&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and &lt;b&gt;lst2&lt;/b&gt;.<br>6. Update a dictionary and add the &lt;b&gt;key&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;designation&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;lst3&lt;/b&gt;.<br>Set a default message for a key of your choice.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(109, 'Dictionary Exercises - IV', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>You are going to create a employee database using the learnings<br>of list and dictionary. This time you are going for 2 companies.</p><p>Write a code that does he following:</p><p>1. Create a list of employee names named as &lt;b&gt;lst1.&lt;/b&gt;<br>2. Create a list of employee city named as &lt;b&gt;lst2.&lt;/b&gt;<br>3. Create a list of employee designation named as &lt;b&gt;lst3.&lt;/b&gt;<br>4. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;keys&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;Employee Names&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>, &lt;b&gt;Employee City&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;Employee Designation&lt;/b&gt; .<br>5. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>as &lt;b&gt;lst1&lt;/b&gt;, &lt;b&gt;lst2&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;lst3&lt;/b&gt;.<br>6. Create a list of employee names named as &lt;b&gt;lst4.&lt;/b&gt;<br>7. Create a list of employee city named as &lt;b&gt;lst5.&lt;/b&gt;<br>8. Create a list of employee designation named as &lt;b&gt;lst6.&lt;/b&gt;<br>9. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d2&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;keys&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;Employee Names&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>, &lt;b&gt;Employee City&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;Employee Designation&lt;/b&gt; .<br>10. Define a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d2&lt;/b&gt; using &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>as &lt;b&gt;lst4&lt;/b&gt;, &lt;b&gt;lst5&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;lst6&lt;/b&gt;.<br>11. Create a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d3&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp;using &lt;b&gt;keys&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;Company1&lt;/b&gt;<br>and &lt;b&gt;Company2&lt;/b&gt;.<br>12. Create a dictionary &lt;b&gt;d3&lt;/b&gt; &nbsp;using &lt;b&gt;values&lt;/b&gt; as &lt;b&gt;d1&lt;/b&gt;<br>and &lt;b&gt;d2&lt;/b&gt; and print the dictionary d3.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(110, 'Set', 'Python', '<p>Python &lt;b&gt;Set&lt;/b&gt; data type is a unique way of data is stored.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Some important points:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>1. They store objects neither by &lt;b&gt;index&lt;/b&gt; nor using a &lt;b&gt;key&lt;/b&gt;.<br>2. They don&#x27;t store the data in any particular order.<br>3. Sets are &lt;b&gt;immutable.&lt;/b&gt;<br>4. They only allow &lt;b&gt;unique values&lt;/b&gt;.<br>5. Since, there is no index or key involved there is no direct&nbsp;<br>way of accessing the data stored in a set.<br><br>Though, there are ways of accessing the data from the set which will be<br>discussed in the later part of the course.</p><p>It is used in a Python program where the programmer would want the values&nbsp;<br>stored in the set to be unchanged and/or avoid duplicate values.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(111, 'Set Operations', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first set and look at few basic operations.</p><p>They are defined using &lt;b&gt;curly brackets {}&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; set_name = {element1,element2,element3...}</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a set using {}<br>set1 = {1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set1)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a set using set keyword<br>set2 = set([&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7])</p><p>print(set2)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Only unique values are allowed<br>set3 = {1,2,2,2,2,234,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set3)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>set4 = {&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1}</p><p>#This will cause an error&nbsp;<br>print(set4)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining an empty set<br>set_empty = set({})</p><p>print(set_empty)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(112, 'Set Methods - I', 'Python', '<p>Just like strings, list and other objects set contains a number of useful methods&nbsp;<br>that is useful for any programmer.</p><p>For a set defined as &lt;b&gt;S&lt;/b&gt; the syntax will be as below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.method()</p><p>1. &lt;b&gt;.add()&lt;/b&gt; - Adds an element or a tuple to the set.<br>2. &lt;b&gt;.pop()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes the element from the set.<br>3. &lt;b&gt;.copy()&lt;/b&gt; - Creates a copy of the set.<br>4. &lt;b&gt;.clear()&lt;/b&gt; - Removing all the elements from the set.<br>5. &lt;b&gt;.discard()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes a specified element from the set.<br>6. &lt;b&gt;.remove()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes a specified element from the set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>The difference between &lt;b&gt;.setdiscard()&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;.remove()&lt;/b&gt; method&nbsp;<br>will be discussed later in the course.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons. Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2');
INSERT INTO `courses` (`id`, `course_topic`, `course_category`, `course_data`, `course_color`, `hints`, `answer`, `cat_id`) VALUES
(113, '.add() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.keys()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.add()&lt;/b&gt; - Adds the desired element to the set</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.add(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>This only adds &lt;b&gt;individual element or a tuple&lt;/b&gt; to the set and can&#x27;t add objects like&nbsp;<br>list or a dictionary etc.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Adding an element<br>set1.add(&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Adding an element<br>set1.add(50)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Adding a Tuple<br>set1.add((1,2,3,4))</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Adding a Tuple<br>set1.add((&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;))</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Can&#x27;t add a dictionary or a list<br>#Running the below lines will cause an error<br>set1.add([1,2,3,4])</p><p>set1.add({&#x27;k1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;k2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;})</p><p>print(set1)<br>#--------------------------------------</p>', 'White (normal card)', '', '', '2'),
(114, '.pop() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method <strong>.pop()</strong></p><p><strong>.pop()</strong> - Removes the desired element to the set</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong> S.pop()</p><p><strong>Note:</strong><br>This only removes the <strong>elements</strong> from left to right order.</p><p>User can&#x27;t <strong>specify</strong> the element for the removal.</p><p><strong>Copy the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Adding an element<br>set1.pop()</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Adding an element<br>set1.add(50)</p><p>set1.pop()</p><p>print(set1)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(115, '.copy() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.copy()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.copy()&lt;/b&gt; - Creates a copy of the set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.copy()</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Adding an element<br>set2 = set1.copy()</p><p>print(set2)</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(116, '.clear() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the &lt;b&gt;.clear()&lt;/b&gt; method.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.clear()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes all the elements from the set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.clear()</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Clear method<br>set1.clear()</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Clear method<br>set2.clear()</p><p>print(set2)<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(117, '.discard() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.discard()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.discard()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes a specified element from the set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.discard(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>If this method finds the specified in the set it will remove it.<br>If it doesn&#x27;t find it will continue with the remaining program&nbsp;<br>statements.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Removing a set&nbsp;<br>set1.discard(5)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Discarding an element which is not there in the set<br>set2.discard(5)</p><p>print(set2)</p><p>print(\\\"Discard method produce no errors\\\")</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(118, '.remove() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.remove()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.remove()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes a specified element from the set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.remove(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>If this method finds the specified in the set it will remove it.<br>If it doesn&#x27;t find it will not continue with the remaining program&nbsp;<br>statements and raise an error.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Removing an element<br>set1.remove(5)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;, &#x27;Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Removing an element which is not there in the set<br>set2.remove(5)</p><p>print(set2)</p><p>print(\\\"You won&#x27;t see this message\\\")</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(119, 'Set Methods - II', 'Python', '<p>Some more dictionary methods.</p><p>For a set defined as &lt;b&gt;S&lt;/b&gt; the syntax will be as below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.method()</p><p>1. &lt;b&gt;.union()&lt;/b&gt; - Performs the union operations on the specified set.<br>2. &lt;b&gt;.intersection()&lt;/b&gt; - Performs the intersection operations on the specified set.<br>3. &lt;b&gt;.issubset()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether one or more sets are subsets of another set.<br>4. &lt;b&gt;.issuperset()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether a set is a superset for one or more sets.<br>5. &lt;b&gt;.difference()&lt;/b&gt; - Prints the elements that exist only in the first set, and not in both sets.<br>6. &lt;b&gt;.isdisjoint()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether there are any common elements between two sets.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>The difference between &lt;b&gt;.setdiscard()&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;.remove()&lt;/b&gt; method&nbsp;<br>will be discussed later in the course.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(120, '.union() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method <strong>.union()</strong></p><p><strong>.union()</strong> - Performs the union operations on the specified set.</p><p>Syntax: S.union(set1,set2...)</p><p><strong>Copy the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Union method<br>set3 = set1.union(set2)</p><p>#Notice the order of elements<br>#set2 elements will be added to the set1<br>print(set3)</p><p>#Union method<br>set4 = set2.union(set1)</p><p>#Notice the order of elements<br>#set1 elements will be added to the set2<br>print(set4)</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set5 = {6,7,8,9}</p><p>#Union method for multiple sets<br>set6 &nbsp;= set1.union(set2,set5)</p><p>print(set6)</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(121, '.intersection() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.intersection()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.intersection()&lt;/b&gt; - Performs the intersection operations on the specified set.</p><p>Syntax: S.intersection(set1,set2...)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Intersection method<br>print(set1.intersection(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Intersection method<br>print(set1.intersection(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {4,5,100,200,300,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#Intersection method<br>print(set1.intersection(set2,set3))<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(122, '.issubset() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.issubset()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;Note:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;<br>A &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt; is a subset of another &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt; if all&nbsp;<br>elements of the &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt; are elements of the &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.issubset()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether one or more sets are subsets of another set.</p><p>Syntax: S.issubset(set1)</p><p>It returns a &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt; value.</p><p>For above mentioned example,&nbsp;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is a subset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is not a subset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt;</p><p><br>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#issubset method<br>print(set1.issubset(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {1,2}</p><p>#issubset method<br>print(set3.issubset(set1))<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(123, '.issuperset() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.issuperset()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;Note:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;<br>If &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt; is a proper superset of &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt;, then all elements of&nbsp;<br>&lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt; are in &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt; but &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt; contains at least&nbsp;<br>one element that is not in &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.issuperset()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether a set is a superset to another set or not.</p><p>Syntax: S.issuperset(set1)</p><p>It returns a &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt; value.</p><p>For above mentioned example,&nbsp;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is a superset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is not a superset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt;</p><p><br>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#issuperset method<br>print(set1.issuperset(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {1,2}</p><p>#issuperset method<br>print(set1.issuperset(set3))<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(124, '.issuperset() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method <strong>.issuperset()</strong></p><p><strong>Note:</strong><br>If <strong>set B</strong> is a proper superset of <strong>set A</strong>, then all elements of&nbsp;<br><strong>set A</strong> are in <strong>set B</strong> but <strong>set B</strong> contains at least&nbsp;<br>one element that is not in <strong>set A</strong>.</p><p><strong>.issuperset()</strong> - Checks whether a set is a superset to another set or not.</p><p>Syntax: S.issuperset(set1)</p><p>It returns a <strong>TRUE</strong> or <strong>FALSE</strong> value.</p><p>For above mentioned example,&nbsp;<br>if &nbsp;<strong>set S</strong> is a superset of <strong>set1</strong> then it will return <strong>TRUE</strong><br>if &nbsp;<strong>set S</strong> is not a superset of <strong>set1</strong> then it will return <strong>FALSE</strong></p><p><br><strong>Copy the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#issuperset method<br>print(set1.issuperset(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {1,2}</p><p>#issuperset method<br>print(set1.issuperset(set3))<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(125, '.issubset() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.issubset()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;Note:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;<br>A &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt; is a subset of another &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt; if all&nbsp;<br>elements of the &lt;b&gt;set A&lt;/b&gt; are elements of the &lt;b&gt;set B&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.issubset()&lt;/b&gt; - Checks whether one or more sets are subsets of another set.</p><p>Syntax: S.issubset(set1)</p><p>It returns a &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt; or &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt; value.</p><p>For above mentioned example,&nbsp;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is a subset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;TRUE&lt;/b&gt;<br>if &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;set S&lt;/b&gt; is not a subset of &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; then it will return &lt;b&gt;FALSE&lt;/b&gt;</p><p><br>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>#issubset method<br>print(set1.issubset(set2))</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {1,2}</p><p>#issubset method<br>print(set3.issubset(set1))<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(126, 'Set Methods - III', 'Python', '<p>Some more dictionary methods.</p><p>For a set defined as <strong>S</strong> the syntax will be as below:</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong> S.method()</p><p>1. <strong>.union()</strong> - Performs the union operations on the specified set.<br>2. <strong>.intersection()</strong> - Performs the intersection operations on the specified set.<br>3. <strong>.issubset()</strong> - Checks whether one or more sets are subsets of another set.<br>4. <strong>.issuperset()</strong> - Checks whether a set is a superset for one or more sets.<br>5. <strong>.difference()</strong> - Prints the elements that exist only in the first set, and not in both sets.<br>6. <strong>.isdisjoint()</strong> - Checks whether there are any common elements between two sets.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong><br>The difference between <strong>.setdiscard()</strong> and <strong>.remove()</strong> method&nbsp;<br>will be discussed later in the course.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(127, '.update() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.update()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.update()&lt;/b&gt; - Adds any individual element and/or objects&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; such as list, dictionary, tuple or set.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.update(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>set1.update(set2)</p><p>#update method<br>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [10,20,30,40]</p><p>#update method<br>set1.update(lst)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:10,&#x27;b&#x27;:20,&#x27;c&#x27;:30,&#x27;d&#x27;:40}</p><p>#update method<br>set1.update(d1)</p><p>#Do note the way dictionary is added<br>print(set1)<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:10,&#x27;b&#x27;:20,&#x27;c&#x27;:30,&#x27;d&#x27;:40}</p><p>#update method<br>set1.update(d1,lst)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:10,&#x27;b&#x27;:20,&#x27;c&#x27;:30,&#x27;d&#x27;:40}</p><p>#update method<br>set1.update(d1,lst,&#x27;Python&#x27;)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(128, '.symmetric_difference() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.symmetric_difference()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.symmetric_difference()&lt;/b&gt; - Prints elements that are present in both the&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; sets but not present in their intersection.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.symmetric_difference(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5,10,20,30}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {1,2,3,4,5,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>set3 = set1.symmetric_difference(set2)</p><p>#symmetric_difference method<br>print(set3)</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(129, '.symmetric_difference_update() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.symmetric_difference_update()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.symmetric_difference()&lt;/b&gt; - Prints elements that are present in both the&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; sets but not present in their intersection.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; S.symmetric_difference(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5,10,20,30}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {1,2,3,4,5,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Learning&#x27;}</p><p>set3 = set1.symmetric_difference_update(set2)</p><p>#symmetric_difference_update method<br>print(set3)</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(130, '.difference_update() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.difference_update()&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.difference_update()&lt;/b&gt; - Removes an item or items that<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;is present in both elements.</p><p>Syntax: S.difference_update(set1,set2...)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {1,2,3,4,5,6}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {1,2}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {4,5}</p><p>#difference_update method for multiple sets<br>set1.difference_update(set2,set3)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set1 = {&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;C language&#x27;,&#x27;C++&#x27;, &#x27;Java Script&#x27;}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set2 = {&#x27;HTML&#x27;,&#x27;CSS&#x27;}</p><p>#Defining a set<br>set3 = {&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;C language&#x27;}</p><p>#difference_update method for multiple sets<br>set1.difference_update(set2,set3)</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(131, 'Set Exercises - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><p>1. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt;containing<br>&nbsp;&lt;b&gt;5 fruits&lt;/b&gt; containing &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;Orange, Apple, Banana, Mango, Watermelon&lt;/b&gt;.<br>2. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set2&lt;/b&gt; containing&nbsp;<br>&lt;b&gt;5 vegetables&lt;/b&gt; containing &lt;b&gt;Cucumber, Tomato, Onion, Carrot, Okra&lt;/b&gt;.<br>3. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set3&lt;/b&gt;by &lt;b&gt;adding&lt;/b&gt; set1 and set2.<br>4. Write code to remove &lt;b&gt;Orange, Apple and Banana&lt;/b&gt; from &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt;<br>using the &lt;b&gt;pop method&lt;/b&gt;.<br>5. Clear the &lt;b&gt;set3&lt;/b&gt;.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(132, 'Set Exercises - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><p>1. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt;containing<br>&nbsp;&lt;b&gt;5 cities&lt;/b&gt; containing &nbsp;&lt;b&gt;New York, Baden, Zurich, Ahmedabad, Paris&lt;/b&gt;.<br>2. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set2&lt;/b&gt; containing&nbsp;<br>&lt;b&gt;5 countries&lt;/b&gt; containing &lt;b&gt;USA, Switzerland, France, India, UK/b&gt;.<br>3. Define a set named &lt;b&gt;set3&lt;/b&gt;by &lt;b&gt;unionizing &lt;/b&gt; set1 and set2.<br>4. Print the intersection of &lt;b&gt;set3&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>5. Check whether &lt;b&gt;set1&lt;/b&gt; is a &lt;b&gt;subset&lt;/b&gt; of &lt;b&gt;set2&lt;/b&gt;.<br>6. Check whether &lt;b&gt;set3&lt;/b&gt; is a &lt;b&gt;superset&lt;/b&gt; of &lt;b&gt;set2&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(133, 'Set Exercises - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><p>1. Define a set named <strong>set1</strong>containing<br>&nbsp;<strong>5 cities</strong> containing &nbsp;<strong>New York, Baden, Zurich, Ahmedabad, Paris</strong>.<br>2. Define a set named <strong>set2</strong> containing&nbsp;<br><strong>5 countries</strong> containing <strong>USA, Switzerland, France, India, UK/b&gt;.</strong><br><strong>3. Define a set named set3containing</strong><br><strong>&nbsp;5 fruits containing &nbsp;Orange, Apple, Banana, Mango, Watermelon.</strong><br><strong>4. Define a set named set4 containing&nbsp;</strong><br><strong>5 vegetables containing Cucumber, Tomato, Onion, Carrot, Okra.</strong><br><strong>5. Define a set named set5by unionizing set1, set2 and set3.</strong><br><strong>6. Print the difference between set5 and set1</strong><br><strong>7. Are set4 and set3 disjoint sets?</strong><br><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(134, 'Tuple', 'Python', '<p>The tuple object is similar to a list, that cannot be changed.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Some important points:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>1. They store objects by &lt;b&gt;index&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;relative position&lt;/b&gt;.<br>2. Sets are &lt;b&gt;immutable.&lt;/b&gt;<br>3. Tuples are &lt;b&gt;ordered collections&lt;/b&gt; of &lt;b&gt;arbitrary objects&lt;/b&gt;.<br>4. They are &lt;b&gt;heterogeneous&lt;/b&gt; and can store all types of objects.</p><p>It is used in a Python program where the programmer would want the values&nbsp;<br>stored in the tuple to be unchanged.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(135, 'Tuple Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first tuple and look at few basic operations.</p><p>They are defined using &lt;b&gt;round brackets ()&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; tuple_name = (element1,element2,element3...)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>print(tuple2)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>tuple4 = (&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1)</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining an empty set<br>tuple_empty = tuple()</p><p>print(tuple_empty)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(136, 'Tuple Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some more tuple operations.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple using &#x27;+&#x27; operator<br>tuple3 = tuple1 + tuple2</p><p>print(tuple3)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Repetition of elements<br>tuple3 = tuple1 * 5</p><p>print(tuple3)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Checking whether an element belongs to a tuple<br>print(&#x27;Python&#x27; in tuple3)</p><p>print(&#x27;Russia&#x27; in tuple3)<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(137, 'Tuple Methods', 'Python', '<p>Just like strings, list and other objects tuple contains a number of useful methods&nbsp;<br>that is useful for any programmer.</p><p>For a set defined as &lt;b&gt;T&lt;/b&gt; the syntax will be as below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt; T.method()</p><p>1. &lt;b&gt;.count()&lt;/b&gt; - Returns number of times an element appears in the tuple.<br>2. &lt;b&gt;.index()&lt;/b&gt; - Returns the index of an element in the tuple.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(138, '.count() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.count()&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.count()&lt;/b&gt; - Returns number of times an element appears in the tuple.</p><p>Syntax: T.count(element)</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>#Count method<br>tuple1.count(&#x27;Python&#x27;)<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(139, '.index() method', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the method &lt;b&gt;.index()&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;.index()&lt;/b&gt; - Returns the index of an element in the tuple.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining a tuple<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,34,34,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>#index method<br>print(tuple1.index(&#x27;Python&#x27;))<br>#--------------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(140, 'Tuple Slicing - I', 'Python', '<p>We store data to use it at a later point in time.</p><p>Let&#x27;s focus on how we can use tuple slicing to extract the store data.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Always remember that Python starts indexing with 0.&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>Create a &lt;b&gt;5 element&lt;/b&gt; tuple of your choice name it to &lt;b&gt;&#x27;tuple1&#x27;&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>Then, copy the following code and run it.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#---------------------------------------</p><p>print(tuple1[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the tuple<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(141, 'Tuple Slicing - II', 'Python', '<p>We may not always want single elements but may need to a &lt;b&gt;print&lt;/b&gt; a bunch of elements.<br>Then our syntax slightly changes.</p><p>Create a &lt;b&gt;10 element&lt;/b&gt; tuple of your choice name it &lt;b&gt;&#x27;tuple1&#x27;&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>We use &lt;b&gt;:&lt;/b&gt; to specify a range.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>Always remember that the number after the column is ignored.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#---------------------------------------</p><p>print(tuple1[2:7]) #Prints the 3rd to 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(tuple1[:7]) #Prints all the elements till 7th element excluding the 7th</p><p>print(tuple1[3:]) #Prints all the elements from 3rd to the end of the tuple<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(142, 'Tuple Slicing - III', 'Python', '<p>So far we have used only positive numbers in for displaying the elements in the &lt;b&gt;tuple&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>Python also has something called the &lt;b&gt;Negative Indexing&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>Create a &lt;b&gt;10 element&lt;/b&gt; list of your choice name it &lt;b&gt;&#x27;tuple1&#x27;&lt;/b&gt;, then copy the code below:</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>Always remember that the number after the column is ignored.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#---------------------------------------</p><p>print(tuple1[-1])<br>#Prints the last element</p><p>print(tuple1[-5]) &nbsp;<br>#Prints the 6th element from the backwards</p><p>print(tuple1[-5:-3])&nbsp;<br>#Prints the 3rd to 5th element from the backwards</p><p>print(tuple1[-5:])<br>#Prints all the elements to 5th element from the backwards including the 5th</p><p>print(tuple1[:-3])<br>#Prints all the elements from 3rd element till the very first element excluding the 3rd element<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(143, 'Tuple Slicing - IV', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s talk about &lt;b&gt;out-of-bounds&lt;/b&gt; error.</p><p>As we learnt previously, &lt;b&gt;tuple&lt;/b&gt; store data in an order.</p><p>So what if we try to request to print an element which is<br>not there in the tuple.</p><p>We get something called as &lt;b&gt;out-of-bounds&lt;/b&gt; error.</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the code below:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#---------------------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>tuple1 = (1,2,3,4,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;Apple&#x27;)</p><p>#Printing the 7th element in the list<br>print(tuple1[7])</p><p>#Do observe the error.<br>#Since we only have six elements we can&#x27;t Python to print the 7th element.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(144, 'Tuple Exercise - I', 'Python', '<p>Create a &lt;b&gt;tuple&lt;/b&gt; of 15 elements named as &lt;b&gt;tuple1&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>using user input print the all the elements at&nbsp;<br>odd index positions.</p><p>Use positive indexing method.</p><p>Don&#x27;t leave an enter between two lines of code</p><p>Always remember, python starts indexing with &lt;b&gt;0&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>print(tuple1[0])<br>print(tuple1[2])<br>print(tuple1[4])<br>print(tuple1[6])<br>print(tuple1[8])<br>print(tuple1[10])<br>print(tuple1[12])<br>print(tuple1[14])<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(145, 'Tuple Exercise - II', 'Python', '<p>Create a &lt;b&gt;tuple&lt;/b&gt; of 15 elements named as &lt;b&gt;tuple1&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>using user input print the all the elements at&nbsp;<br>odd index positions.</p><p><br>Use positive indexing method.</p><p>Don&#x27;t leave an enter between two lines of code.</p><p>print(tuple1[0])<br>print(tuple1[2])<br>print(tuple1[4])<br>print(tuple1[6])<br>print(tuple1[8])<br>print(tuple1[10])<br>print(tuple1[12])<br>print(tuple1[14])<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(146, 'Tuple Exercise - III', 'Python', '<p>Create a &lt;b&gt;tuple&lt;/b&gt; of 15 elements named &lt;b&gt;tuple1&lt;/b&gt;<br>Using user input.<br><br>Print the all the elements at even positions using negative indexing.</p><p>Use negative indexing method.</p><p>Don&#x27;t leave an enter between two lines of code.</p><p>print(tuple1[-1])<br>print(tuple1[-3])<br>print(tuple1[-5])<br>print(tuple1[-7])<br>print(tuple1[-9])<br>print(tuple1[-11])<br>print(tuple1[-13])<br>print(tuple1[15])</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(147, 'Tuple Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Basically, the nesting of tuple is putting a tuple within a tuple.</p><p>That allows the user to store the data in a multi-layer basis.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax&lt;/b&gt;:</p><p>tuple_name[index][index]...[index]</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the below code:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;))</p><p>#Accessing the tuple (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p><br>Run the copied code and observe the output.</p><p>#-------------------------<br>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;))</p><p>#Accessing the tuple (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(148, 'Tuple Nesting - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s try something more complex</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax&lt;/b&gt;:</p><p>tuple_name[index][index]...[index]</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the below code:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,(&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;)))</p><p>#Accessing thetuple (&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the tuple (&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2][1])</p><p><br>Run the copied code and observe the output.</p><p><br>#-------------------------<br>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,(&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;)))</p><p>#Accessing thetuple (&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the tuple (&#x27;orange&#x27;,&#x27;banana&#x27;,&#x27;apple&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2][1])</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(149, 'Tuple Nesting Exercises', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Let&#x27;s imagine you have a tuple as below:</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,(123,146,(&#x27;56$1&#x27;,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,(&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,(&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;))),211))</p><p>#Task<br>Write a code that does the following.</p><p>1. Define the above tuple<br>2. Write a code that prints &#x27;Orange&#x27;<br>3. Write a code that prints &#x27;Chicago&#x27;<br>4. Write a code that prints &#x27;Python&#x27;</p><p>Use the nested list approach.&nbsp;<br>Don&#x27;t leave any gap between two consecutive lines of code.<br>statement1<br>statement2</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,(123123,1456,(&#x27;546$21&#x27;,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,<br>(&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,(&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;))),21321))<br>print(tuple1[4][2][2])<br>print(tuple1[4][2][3][2])<br>print(tuple1[4][2][3][4][2])</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(150, 'Statements', 'Python', '<p>So far we have learnt about Python&#x27;s built-in objects.</p><p>It&#x27;s time to learn about statements. To be more specific, conditional statements.</p><p>So, what are &lt;b&gt;statements&lt;/b&gt; anyway?</p><p>In simple terms, statements are the things<br>you write to tell Python what your programs<br>should do.</p><p>Less informally, Python is a procedural, statement-based language.</p><p>By combining statements, you specify a procedure that Python&nbsp;<br>performs to satisfy a program’s goals.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(151, 'Conditional Statements', 'Python', '<p>In case a program with thousands of lines of code, it may not be required to execute the entire program<br>line by line.</p><p>It may be the case that we may only need to execute a part or some parts of the program.</p><p>Further, it may so happen that needs to be done in a particular order.</p><p>So basically, we are controlling the flow of the program (execution) based on certain needs or&nbsp;<br>less informally, conditions.</p><p>This is where we use Python&#x27;s conditional statements.</p><p>For now, we will be looking at the &lt;b&gt;if&lt;/b&gt; statement.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.<br><br><br>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>Do notice the indentation (gap) between&nbsp;<br>the &lt;b&gt;if&lt;/b&gt; line and the &lt;b&gt;Statements&lt;/b&gt; line.</p><p><br><br><br>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(152, 'Indentation', 'Python', '<p>Before, understanding the indentation let&#x27;s look at the general structure<br>of the &lt;b&gt;if&lt;/b&gt; statement.</p><p>We promise after this we will get into action with the &lt;b&gt;if&lt;/b&gt; statement.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.</p><p>or looking at the more generic form</p><p>Header block:<br>Statement block<br>&nbsp;</p><p>What is &lt;b&gt;indentation&lt;/b&gt; in Python?</p><p>Indentation is the gap that is provided between a &lt;b&gt;Header block&lt;/b&gt;&nbsp;<br>and a &lt;b&gt;Statement block&lt;/b&gt;.</p><p>Why &lt;b&gt;indentation&lt;/b&gt; in Python?</p><p>It’s one of the main ways that Python almost forces programmers to&nbsp;<br>produce uniform, regular, and readable code.</p><p>It essentially means that you must line up your code vertically, in columns, according<br>to its logical structure.</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(153, 'if Statement - I', 'Python', '<p>&lt;b&gt;Syntax:&lt;/b&gt;</p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Some points on the indentation:&lt;/b&gt;<br>1. Technically, Python doesn’t care &lt;b&gt;how you indent (tabs or spaces).&lt;/b&gt;<br>2. Technically, Python doesn’t care &lt;b&gt;how much you indent (tabs or spaces).&lt;/b&gt;<br>3. The indentation of one nested block can be totally different from that of another.<br>4. The&lt;b&gt;syntax rule&lt;/b&gt; is only that for a given single statement block,&nbsp;<br>all of its statements must be &lt;b&gt;indented the same distance to the right&lt;/b&gt;.<br><br>&lt;b&gt;Note:&lt;/b&gt;<br>It is advisable to select either a &lt;b&gt;tab&lt;/b&gt; or a &lt;b&gt;space&lt;/b&gt; as a indentation preference.</p><p>For the entire course we are going to use a &lt;b&gt;single tab&lt;/b&gt; as a our indentation preference.<br><br><br>&lt;b&gt;Copy the below code:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining variables<br>a = 5</p><p>b =10</p><p>#--------------------------------------<br>#Indentation = Single Space<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(a)&nbsp;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Indentation = Single Tab<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(a)&nbsp;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Indentation = 5 Spaces<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(a)&nbsp;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Indentation = 5 Tabs<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(a)&nbsp;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Indentation = 1 Space and 1 tab<br>#This will give you error<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(a)<br>print(b)<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Different Indentation<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(\\\"This is a space indented block\\\")</p><p>if a&gt;b:<br>print(\\\"This is a tab indented block\\\")&nbsp;<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(154, 'if Statement - II', 'Python', '<p>In the process of learning about the indentation you have accomplished 2 things:</p><p>1. Mastering the syntax of if statement.<br>2. Building your first if statement.</p><p>Trust us, that &lt;b&gt;if statement&lt;/b&gt; has much more to offer.</p><p>So let&#x27;s begin with simple &lt;b&gt;if&lt;/b&gt; statements.</p><p>Python&#x27;s objective is to make programmers&#x27; lives simple that is why it has structures that<br>requires minimum typing.</p><p>&lt;b&gt;Copy the below code:&lt;/b&gt;<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining variables</p><p>a = 5</p><p>b =[1,2,4,5]</p><p>c =[&#x27;Orange&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Banana&#x27;, &#x27;Papaya&#x27;]<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement<br>if a&gt;0:<br>print(\\\"I am learning Python.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with keyword in<br>if 5 in b:<br>print(\\\"List contains a 5.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with keyword in<br>if &#x27;Papaya&#x27; in c:<br>print(\\\"List contains a Papaya.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;==&#x27; operator<br>if a== 5:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is 5.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;!=&#x27; operator<br>if a!= 6:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is not 6.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;4:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is greater than 4.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;=&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;=0:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is greater than or equal to 0.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;7:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is less than 7.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;=&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;=100:<br>print(\\\"Value of a is greater than or equal 100.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2'),
(155, 'if Statement - III', 'Python', '<p>Evaluating multiple conditions at once with only the if statement.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>if (condition1) logical/comparison operator (condition2):<br>Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.</p><p><br><strong>Copy the below code:</strong><br>#--------------------------------------<br>#Defining variables</p><p>a = 6</p><p>b =[1,2,4,5]</p><p>c =[&#x27;Orange&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Banana&#x27;, &#x27;Papaya&#x27;]<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement<br>#Execute the statements when both conditions are met<br>if (a&gt;0) and (a&lt;10):<br>print(\\\"I am learning Python.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with keyword in<br>#Execute the statements when both conditions are met<br>if (5 in b) and (2 in b):<br>print(\\\"List contains a 5 and 2.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with multiple conditions&nbsp;<br>#Execute the statements when either of the conditions are met<br>if (&#x27;Papaya&#x27; in c) or (&#x27;Peach&#x27; in c):<br>print(\\\"List contains a Papaya or Papaya.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with multiple conditions&nbsp;<br>if (a==5) and (len(b)&lt;=5):<br>print(\\\"Value of a is 5 and length of b is less than equal to 5.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with multiple conditions&nbsp;<br>if (a!= 6) and (a&gt;0) and (a&lt;10):<br>print(\\\"Value of a is not 6 but greater than 0 and less than 10.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with multiple conditions&nbsp;<br>if (a&gt;4) or (a&lt;10) or (a!=100):<br>print(\\\"This is how multiple conditions are evaluated.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;%&#x27; operator<br>if (a%2 equals to 0):<br>print(\\\"a is an even number.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------<br>#if statement with &#x27;%&#x27; operator<br>if (a%2 is not 0):<br>print(\\\"a is an odd number.\\\")<br>#--------------------------------------</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '2');
