(284, 'Key concepts for programming', 'Python', '<p><strong>What is Programming?</strong></p><ul><li>Computer programming is the process of designing and building an executable computer program to accomplish a specific computing result or to perform a specific task.</li></ul><p><strong>What is a Module?</strong></p><ul><li>A module is a software component or part of a program that contains one or more routines. Many modules form a program.</li></ul><p><strong>What is a statement?&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li>In computer programming, a statement is a syntactic unit of an imperative programming language that expresses some action to be carried out.</li></ul><p><strong>What is an expression?&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li>The term expression means a computer program statement that evaluates to some value.</li></ul><p><strong>What is a data structure?&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li>A data structure is a way of organizing the data so that it can be used efficiently.</li></ul><p><strong>What is an algorithm?&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li>A programming algorithm is a procedure or formula used for solving a problem.</li></ul><p><strong>What is a data type?&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li>A data type or simply sometime referred to as a type is an attribute of data which tells the compiler or interpreter how the programmer intends to use the data.</li></ul>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(285, 'Built-in object types in Python', 'Python', '<p>Following table shows the built-in objects in Python.</p><figure class=\\\"table\\\"><table><thead><tr><th><i>Object Type</i></th><th><i>Examples</i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Numbers</td><td>1234, 3.1415, 3+4j, 0b111, Decimal(), Fraction()</td></tr><tr><td>Strings</td><td>&#x27;spam&#x27;, Bob&#x27;s, b&#x27;ax01c&#x27;, u&#x27;spxc4m&#x27;</td></tr><tr><td>Lists</td><td>[1, [2, &#x27;three&#x27;], 4.5], list(range(10))</td></tr><tr><td>Dictionaries</td><td>{&#x27;food&#x27;: &#x27;spam&#x27;, &#x27;taste&#x27;: &#x27;yum&#x27;}, dict(hours=10)</td></tr><tr><td>Tuples</td><td>(1, &#x27;spam&#x27;, 4, &#x27;U&#x27;), tuple(&#x27;spam&#x27;), namedtuple</td></tr><tr><td>Files</td><td>open(&#x27;eggs.txt&#x27;), open(r&#x27;C:ham.bin&#x27;, &#x27;wb&#x27;)</td></tr><tr><td>Sets</td><td>set(&#x27;abc&#x27;), {&#x27;a&#x27;, &#x27;b&#x27;, &#x27;c&#x27;}</td></tr><tr><td>Other core types</td><td>Booleans, types, None</td></tr><tr><td>Program unit types</td><td>Functions, modules, classes</td></tr><tr><td>Implementation-related types</td><td>Compiled code, stack tracebacks</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(286, 'Basics - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s get you started with the basics!</p><p>One of the most commonly used feature in Python is the <strong>print</strong> feature.</p><p>&#x27;print&#x27; is used to well print something on the screen.&nbsp;</p><p>That can be anything, from your name to output of a really complex program.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>print(\"Text that you want to print\")</p></blockquote><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>print(\"I am learning Python with Glowworm Academy\")</p><p>print(\"Python is easy\")</p><p>print (\"I am learning the print statement in Python\")</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>print(\"I am learning Python with Glowworm Academy\")</p><p>print(\"Python is easy\")</p><p>print (\"I am learning the print statement in Python\")</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(287, 'Basics Exercise - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s print some stuff to get you comfortable.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>print(\"Python is quite easy!\")</p><p>print(\"1+1 = 2 and Python is that easy!\")</p><p>print(\"I can use special characters also in Python like !@##$%@#%$@#$!@$!@$%^&amp;$*^\")</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><p>print(\"Python is quite easy!\")</p><p>print(\"1+1 = 2 and Python is that easy!\")</p><p>print(\"I can use special characters also in Python like !@##$%@#%$@#$!@$!@$%^&amp;$*^\")</p>', '1'),
(288, 'Basics- II', 'Python', '<p>A code is also a way of communication between two users.&nbsp;</p><p>To have a smooth communication in Python Commenting is quite useful.</p><p>While execution of the code the <strong>Python interpreter</strong> will <strong>ignore</strong> the commented code.</p><p><strong>There are two ways commenting can be done.</strong></p><ul><li>Using the &#x27;#&#x27; sign. What ever you write after the hash will be considered as a comment and will be ignored by Python.</li></ul><blockquote><p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; #Your Comment&nbsp;</p></blockquote><ul><li>Another way is the use of inverted commas.</li></ul><blockquote><p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \"\"\" I am learning how to comment in Python\"\"\"</p></blockquote><p><i><strong>Note:</strong></i></p><p>Bear in mind that<strong> # method</strong> is only good for<strong> single line commenting</strong></p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(289, 'Basics Exercise - II', 'Python', '<p>Make the following statements in comments.</p><p><strong>Single line commenting</strong></p><p>25 *25 = 625</p><p>!@#!@$!@%!@%$@#</p><p>Orange is a fruit.</p><p><strong>Multi-line commenting</strong></p><ol><li>This is a multiline commenting example</li><li>This is a multiline commenting example with special characters&gt;&gt;&gt;@#$%</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Single line commenting</p><p>#25 *25 = 625</p><p>#!@#!@$!@%!@%$@#</p><p>#Orange is a fruit.</p><p>\"\"\"</p><p>Multi-line commenting</p><p>\"\"\"</p><p>\"\"\"</p><p>This is a multiline commenting example</p><p>\"\"\"</p><p>\"\"\"</p><p>This is a multiline commenting example with special characters&gt;&gt;&gt;@#$%</p><p>\"\"\"</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(290, 'Variable - I', 'Python', '<p>Assigning a<strong> variable</strong> is one of the basic operations that any coder has to do.</p><p><strong>Variables </strong>are simply names—created by you or Python—that are used to <strong>keep track of information</strong> in your program.</p><p><strong>Few things to keep in mind while dealing with variables:</strong></p><ul><li>Variables are created when they are first assigned values.</li><li>Variables are replaced with their values when used in expressions.</li><li>Variables must be assigned before they can be used in expressions.</li></ul><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong></p><p>a = 10 #Assigning 10 to a variable named as a</p><p>b = Python\" #Assigning Python to a variable named as b</p><p>c = a #Assigning b to a variable named as a</p><p>#Multiple assignments</p><p>a,b =3,4</p><p>print(\"The value of variable a is : \", a)</p><p>print(\"The value of variable b is : \", b)</p><p>#Variable exchange</p><p>a,b = b,a</p><p>#Printing after exchange</p><p>print(\"The value of variable a is : \", a)</p><p>print(\"The value of variable b is : \", b)</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>a = 10 #Assigning 10 to a variable named as a</p><p>b = Python\" #Assigning Python to a variable named as b</p><p>c = a #Assigning b to a variable named as a</p><p>#Multiple assignments</p><p>a,b =3,4</p><p>print(\"The value of variable a is : \", a)</p><p>print(\"The value of variable b is : \", b)</p><p>#Variable exchange</p><p>a,b = b,a</p><p>#Printing after exchange</p><p>print(\"The value of variable a is : \", a)</p><p>print(\"The value of variable b is : \", b)</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(291, 'Variable - II', 'Python', '<p>It is easy for a newbie to make a mistake while defining a variable.</p><p><strong>Rules for defining variables in Python:&nbsp;</strong></p><ol><li><strong>Must</strong> start with a <strong>letter</strong> or an <strong>underscore</strong>.</li><li><strong>Can&#x27;t start </strong>with a <strong>number</strong> or <strong>any other special characters</strong>.</li><li>Can be defined <strong>only</strong> using <strong>alphanumeric</strong> (A-Z, a-z,0-9) and <strong>underscore</strong>.</li><li><strong>Variables</strong> are <strong>case sensitive</strong>.</li></ol><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>a = 5 #This is a variable</p><p>@name = \"Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>*name = Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>12312test = \"Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>_var1 = 1234 #This is a variable</p><p>#name and NAME are different.</p><p>NAME = 4&nbsp;</p><p>name = 56</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>a = 5 #This is a variable</p><p>@name = \"Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>*name = Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>12312test = \"Python\" #Not a variable</p><p>_var1 = 1234 #This is a variable</p><p>#name and NAME are different.</p><p>NAME = 4</p><p>name = 56</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(292, 'Variable Exercise', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Define and assign and two variables named as var1 and var2</p><p>Print both of them on the screen.</p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining variables</p><p>var1 = \"This is variable 1\"</p><p>var2 = \"This is variable 2\"</p><p>#Printing the variable values</p><p>print(\"The value of variable 1 is: \",var1)</p><p>print(\"The value of variable 2 is: \",var2)</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(293, 'Operators', 'Python', '<p><strong>Operators</strong> are used to perform operations on <strong>variables</strong> and <strong>values</strong>.</p><p>Python contains a lot of operators for different purposes.</p><p><strong>They are as under:</strong></p><ol><li>Arithmetic operators</li><li>Assignment operators</li><li>Comparison operators</li><li>Logical operators</li><li>Identity operators</li><li>Membership operators</li><li>Bitwise operators</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(294, 'Arithmetic Operators', 'Python', '<p>As the name suggests that it is used to perform arithmetic operations their value.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Example</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Use</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>+</td><td>x + y</td><td>Addition</td></tr><tr><td>-</td><td>x - y</td><td>Subtraction</td></tr><tr><td>*</td><td>x * y</td><td>Multiplication</td></tr><tr><td>/</td><td>x / y</td><td>Division</td></tr><tr><td>%</td><td>x % y</td><td>Modulus</td></tr><tr><td>**</td><td>x ** y</td><td>Exponentiation</td></tr><tr><td>//</td><td>x // y</td><td>Floor division</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(295, 'Assignment Operators', 'Python', '<p>As the name suggests that it is used to assign variables their value.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Example</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Alternative</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>=</td><td>x = 5</td><td>x = 10</td></tr><tr><td>+=</td><td>x = x + 3</td><td>x += 1</td></tr><tr><td>-=</td><td>x = x - 3</td><td>x -= 1</td></tr><tr><td>*=</td><td>x = x * 3</td><td>x *= 3</td></tr><tr><td>/=</td><td>x = x / 3</td><td>x /= 3</td></tr><tr><td>%=</td><td>x = x % 3</td><td>x %= 3</td></tr><tr><td>//=</td><td>x = x // 3</td><td>x //= 3</td></tr><tr><td>**=</td><td>x = x ** 3</td><td>x **= 3</td></tr><tr><td>&amp;=</td><td>x = x &amp; 3</td><td>x &amp;= 3</td></tr><tr><td>|=</td><td>x = x | 3</td><td>x |= 3</td></tr><tr><td>^=</td><td>x = x ^ 3</td><td>x ^= 3</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;&gt;=</td><td>x = x &gt;&gt; 3</td><td>x &gt;&gt;= 3</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&lt;=</td><td>x = x &lt;&lt; 3</td><td>x &lt;&lt;= 3</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(296, 'Comparison Operators', 'Python', '<p>As the name suggests that it is used to compare the value of variables.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Example</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Used to check</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>==</td><td>x == y</td><td>Equal</td></tr><tr><td>!=</td><td>x != y</td><td>Not equal</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;</td><td>x &gt; y</td><td>Greater than</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;</td><td>x &lt; y</td><td>Less than</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;=</td><td>x &gt;= y</td><td>Greater than or equal to</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;=</td><td>x &lt;= y</td><td>Less than or equal to</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(297, 'Logical Operators', 'Python', '<p>As the name suggests that it is used to perform logical operations to facilitate decision making/or condition evaluation.&nbsp;</p><p>More on that later in the course.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Use</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Syntax</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>and&nbsp;</td><td>Returns True if both statements are true</td><td>x &lt; 5 and&nbsp; x &lt; 10</td></tr><tr><td>or</td><td>Returns True if one of the statements is true</td><td>x &lt; 5 or x &lt; 4</td></tr><tr><td>not</td><td>Reverse the result, returns False if the result is true</td><td>not(x &lt; 5 and x &lt; 10)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(298, 'Identity Operators', 'Python', '<p>It is used to compare variables and facilitate decision making.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Syntax</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Description</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>is&nbsp;</td><td>x is y</td><td>Returns True if both variables are the same object</td></tr><tr><td>is not</td><td>x is not y</td><td>Returns True if both variables are not the same object</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(299, 'Membership Operators', 'Python', '<p>Simply put used to check, whether something belongs in a certain object or not.&nbsp;</p><p>More on that later.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Syntax</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Description</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>in&nbsp;</td><td>x in y</td><td>Returns True if a sequence with the specified value is present in the object</td></tr><tr><td>not in</td><td>x not in y</td><td>Returns True if a sequence with the specified value is not present in the object</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(300, 'Bitwise Operator', 'Python', '<p>Bitwise operators are used to compare (binary) numbers.&nbsp;</p><p>More on that later.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><i><strong>Operator</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Name</strong></i></td><td><i><strong>Use</strong></i></td></tr><tr><td>&amp;&nbsp;</td><td>AND</td><td>Sets each bit to 1 if both bits are 1</td></tr><tr><td>|</td><td>OR</td><td>Sets each bit to 1 if one of two bits is 1</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;^</td><td>XOR</td><td>Sets each bit to 1 if only one of two bits is 1</td></tr><tr><td>~&nbsp;</td><td>NOT</td><td>Inverts all the bits</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&lt;</td><td>Zero fill left shift</td><td>Shift left by pushing zeros in from the right and let the leftmost bits fall off</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;&gt;</td><td>Signed right shift</td><td>Shift right by pushing copies of the leftmost bit in from the left, and let the rightmost bits fall off</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(301, 'User Input', 'Python', '<p>User input is one of the most important aspects of programming.</p><p>A programmer has to take user input many times in order to perform tasks.</p><p>You can learn about taking input from user in Python from this video:</p><p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/CJfXVwr_vWY\"><strong>https://youtu.be/CJfXVwr_vWY</strong></a></p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>We are committed to the security of the platform and to protect your privacy.</p><p>In order to honor our commitment we are discussing this particular topic through a video.</p><p>All other topics will be covered in an interactive way.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(302, 'User Input Exercise', 'Python', '<p>After learning about how to take input from the user it&#x27;s time to look at an exercise.</p><p>Please go through the video in order to perform that exercise.</p><p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/5LMCS9nG9e4\"><strong>https://youtu.be/5LMCS9nG9e4</strong></a></p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>We are committed to the security of the platform and to protect your privacy.</p><p>In order to honor our commitment we are discussing this particular topic through a video.</p><p>All other topics will be covered in an interactive way.</p>', '', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(303, 'Data types - I', 'Python', '<h4>What is a data type?</h4><p>It is an attribute of data which tells the compiler or interpreter how the programmer intends to use the data.</p><p>Different datatypes in Python are as under.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i><strong>Datatype&nbsp;</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Notations</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Type of data stored</strong></i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Text</td><td>str</td><td>Name, Address</td></tr><tr><td>Numeric</td><td>int, float, complex</td><td>Phone number, Zip code</td></tr><tr><td>Sequence</td><td>list, tuple, range</td><td>List of grocery items and their prices</td></tr><tr><td>Mapping</td><td>dict</td><td>Words with their meanings</td></tr><tr><td>Set</td><td>set, frozenset</td><td>To create a set of elements</td></tr><tr><td>Boolean</td><td>bool</td><td>True or False&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Binary&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td><td>bytes, bytearray, memoryview</td><td>To create a byte object</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(304, 'Data types Exercise - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following</p><ol><li>Store your first name into a variable <strong>str1.</strong></li><li>Store your last name into a variable <strong>str2.</strong></li><li>Store your age into a variable <strong>str3.</strong></li><li>Print the data types of <strong>str1</strong>,<strong> str2 </strong>and<strong> str3.&nbsp;</strong></li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining variables</p><p>integer_a = 10</p><p>float_b= 10.12312</p><p>string_c =&#x27; This is a string variable&#x27;</p><p>#Printing the data types of the variable</p><p>print(\"The data type of integer_a is :\")</p><p>print(type(integer_a)</p><p>print(\"The data type of float_b is :\")</p><p>print(type(float_b)</p><p>print(\"The data type of string_c is :\")</p><p>print(type(string_c&nbsp;)</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(305, 'Keywords', 'Python', '<p><strong>Keywords</strong> also known as<strong> reserved words</strong> in Python are one of the most important building blocks of a Python code.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Keywords</strong> have specific <strong>meaning</strong> and <strong>purpose</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Important points on keywords:&nbsp;</strong></p><ol><li>Always available.</li><li>No need to import them.</li><li>Can’t assign anything to them.</li><li>Can’t be used for any other purpose.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(306, 'Types of Keywords', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at the list of keywords in Python.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i><strong>Keywords</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Example</strong></i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Value</td><td>True, False, None</td></tr><tr><td>Operator&nbsp;</td><td>and, or, not, in, is</td></tr><tr><td>Control Flow&nbsp;</td><td>if, elif, else</td></tr><tr><td>Iteration</td><td>for, while, break, continue, else</td></tr><tr><td>Structure</td><td>def, class, with, as, pass, lambda</td></tr><tr><td>Returning</td><td>return, yield</td></tr><tr><td>Import&nbsp;</td><td>import, from, as</td></tr><tr><td>Exception-Handling</td><td>try, except, raise, finally, else, assert</td></tr><tr><td>Asynchronous Programming</td><td>async, await</td></tr><tr><td>Variable Handling</td><td>del, global, nonlocal</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>We will be learning all of this one by one with their use cases throughout the course not necessarily in any specific order.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(307, 'Keywords list', 'Python', '<p><strong>How to access the entire list?&nbsp;</strong></p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>import keyword&nbsp;</p><p>print(keyword.kwlist)&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote><p><strong>Want help with a built-in object or keyword?</strong></p><blockquote><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>help(keyword)</p></blockquote><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>help(&#x27;print&#x27;)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>import keyword&nbsp;</p><p>print(keyword.kwlist)&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>help(\"print\")</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(308, 'Import Keywords', 'Python', '<p><strong>Import</strong> group of keywords have <strong>three main keywords</strong> within the group:&nbsp;</p><ol><li><strong>import</strong> - Used to import a library/module.</li><li><strong>from</strong> - Used to import a submodule from a library.</li><li><strong>as</strong> - Used to assign a name to the imported library/module. (This will be useful later.)</li></ol><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#Importing the math library&nbsp;</p><p>import math&nbsp;</p><p>#Importing Numpy library as np</p><p>import numpy as np&nbsp;</p><p>#Importing Image module</p><p>from PIL library from PIL import Image</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Importing the math library</p><p>import math</p><p>#Importing Numpy library as np</p><p>import numpy as np</p><p>#Importing Image module</p><p>from PIL library from PIL import Image</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(309, 'Numbers', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s play with numbers. As seen previously Numbers is one of the key objects in Python</p><p>Checkout the following table which is some of the main Numeric data types Python supports.</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i><strong>Types&nbsp;</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Description</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Example</strong></i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Integers</td><td>&nbsp;Numbers not having fractional part</td><td>3,4,5</td></tr><tr><td>Floating</td><td>&nbsp;Numbers having fractional part</td><td>2.8, 3.14</td></tr><tr><td>Complex numbers</td><td>&nbsp;Numbers with imaginary parts</td><td>5 + 6i</td></tr><tr><td>Decimals</td><td>&nbsp;Numbers with fixed precision</td><td>3.4561</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(310, 'Numbers Exercise', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s see how basic mathematical operations are done in Python.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>#Defining the variables</p><p>a = 5</p><p>b = 10</p><p>#Addition of a and b</p><p>c = a+b</p><p>print(\"The addition of a and b is: \", c)</p><p>#Multiplication of a and b</p><p>d = a*b</p><p>print(\"The multiplication of a and b is: \", d)</p><p>#Power of a to the b</p><p>e = a**b</p><p>print(\"The power of a to the b is: \", e)</p><p>#Subtraction of a and b</p><p>f = a-b</p><p>print(\"The subtraction of a and b is: \", f)</p><p>#Division of a and b</p><p>g = a/b</p><p>print(\"The division of a and b is: \", g)</p><p>#Modulo operator of a and b</p><p>h = a%b</p><p>print(\"The remainder of a and b division is: &nbsp;\", h)</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining the variables</p><p>a = 5</p><p>b = 10</p><p>#Addition of a and b</p><p>c = a+b</p><p>print(\"The addition of a and b is: \", c)</p><p>#Multiplication of a and b</p><p>d = a*b</p><p>print(\"The multiplication of a and b is: \", d)</p><p>#Power of a to the b</p><p>e = a**b</p><p>print(\"The power of a to the b is: \", e)</p><p>#Subtraction of a and b</p><p>f = a-b</p><p>print(\"The subtraction of a and b is: \", f)</p><p>#Division of a and b</p><p>g = a/b</p><p>print(\"The division of a and b is: \", g)</p><p>#Modulo operator of a and b</p><p>h = a%b</p><p>print(\"The remainder of a and b division is: &nbsp;\", h)</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(311, 'Iterables', 'Python', '<p>An object capable of returning its members one at a time.</p><p>Two types of iterable exist in Python:</p><ol><li>Sequence type (List, Tuple, String)</li><li>Non-sequence type (Dictionary, Set)</li></ol><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i>No.</i></th><th><i>Type</i></th><th><i>Description</i></th><th><i>Example</i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>List</td><td>An index based data storage mechanism.</td><td>[1,2,&#x27;Python&#x27;]</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Dictionary</td><td>A key bases data storage mechanism.</td><td>{&#x27;a&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;:&#x27;123&#x27;}</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Tuple</td><td>An immutable (fixed) data storage mechanism.</td><td>(1,2,3,4,&#x27;Python&#x27;)</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Set</td><td>An immutable data storage mechanism that can only store unique values.</td><td>{1,2,3,4}</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Iterables can also be defined using the built-in __iter()__ method.</p><p>We are going to learn all of them in an exhaustive manner.</p><p>We will be revisiting this concept along with some advanced topics later again.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(312, 'Strings', 'Python', '<p><strong>Strings</strong> are used to record both<strong> textual information</strong> (your name, for instance) as well as<strong> arbitrary collections of bytes</strong> (such as an image file’s contents).&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Strings</strong> = sequences of one-character strings.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Sequence</strong> = positionally ordered collection of other objects.&nbsp;</p><p>Strings are one of them.&nbsp;</p><p>Sequences maintain a <strong>left-to-right order</strong> among the items they contain their<strong> items are stored and fetched</strong> by their <strong>relative positions</strong>.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the following code:</strong></p><p>print(\"I am learning Python\")</p><p>print(\"I am learning about strings\")</p><p>print(\"Python is easy\")</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>print(\"I am learning Python\")</p><p>print(\"I am learning about strings\")</p><p>print(\"Python is easy\")</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(313, 'Strings Operations- I', 'Python', '<p>There are many important operations a programmer needs to know for strings.&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Evaluating the length of the string</li><li>Extracting/Separating a part of the string</li><li>Concatenation of strings</li><li>Repetition</li></ol><p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Concatenation of strings is related to something called the polymorphism in Python. Which will be discussed in the advance chapters.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(314, 'String Operations Exercise- I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s do some operations:&nbsp;</p><p>Execute each block one by one.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the following code:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Make a 4-character string, and assign it to a name&nbsp;</p><p>S = &#x27;Spam&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Length</p><p>len(S)&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The first item in S, indexing by zero-based position&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;S[0]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The second item from the left&nbsp;</p><p>S[1]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The last item from the end in S</p><p>S[-1]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The second-to-last item from the end</p><p>&nbsp;S[-2] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Slice of S from offsets 1 through 2 (not 3)&nbsp;</p><p>S[1:3]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything past the first</p><p>S[1:] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything but the last</p><p>(1:len(S))&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p>&nbsp;# Following both will have a same output</p><p>S[0:3] &nbsp;</p><p>S[:3]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything but the last again, but simpler (0:-1)</p><p>S[:-1] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># All of S as a top-level copy (0:len(S))</p><p>S[:]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Concatenation S</p><p>&nbsp;S + &#x27;xyz&#x27; &nbsp;# S is unchanged &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Repetition</p><p>S * 8</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------</p><p># Make a 4-character string, and assign it to a name&nbsp;</p><p>S = &#x27;Spam&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Length</p><p>len(S)&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The first item in S, indexing by zero-based position&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;S[0]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The second item from the left&nbsp;</p><p>S[1]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The last item from the end in S</p><p>S[-1]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># The second-to-last item from the end</p><p>&nbsp;S[-2] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Slice of S from offsets 1 through 2 (not 3)&nbsp;</p><p>S[1:3]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything past the first</p><p>S[1:] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything but the last</p><p>(1:len(S))&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p>&nbsp;# Following both will have a same output</p><p>S[0:3] &nbsp;</p><p>S[:3]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Everything but the last again, but simpler (0:-1)</p><p>S[:-1] &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># All of S as a top-level copy (0:len(S))</p><p>S[:]&nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Concatenation S</p><p>&nbsp;S + &#x27;xyz&#x27; &nbsp;# S is unchanged &nbsp;</p><p>#----------------------</p><p># Repetition</p><p>S * 8</p><p>#----------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(315, 'Strings Operations- II', 'Python', '<p><strong>The immutability:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The property of being not editable or being unchangeable.&nbsp;</p><p>Every string operation is defined to produce a new string as its result, because strings are immutable in Python.&nbsp;</p><p>Basically strings cannot be changed in place after they are created.&nbsp;</p><p>Don&#x27;t worry this is not as inefficient as it sounds and there is a way to deal with this problem which we will discuss later.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p><p>S = “Spam&nbsp;</p><p>S[0] = &#x27;z&#x27; # Immutable objects cannot be changed&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Following error will be observed:</strong></p><p>---------------------------------------------------------------------------TypeError &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Traceback (most recent call last) in&nbsp;<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; 3</strong> S =&#x27;Spam&#x27;<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4</strong> ----&gt; 5 S[0] = &#x27;z&#x27; # Immutable objects cannot be changed<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6</strong>&nbsp;<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; 7</strong> #---------------------TypeError: &#x27;str&#x27; object does not support item assignment</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p><p>S = “Spam&nbsp;</p><p>S[0] = &#x27;z&#x27; # Immutable objects cannot be changed&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(316, 'List', 'Python', '<p>Python list object is the most general sequence provided by the language.</p><p>Lists are positionally ordered collections of arbitrarily typed objects without any fixed size.</p><p>They are also mutable and are quite flexible in terms of storage.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong> list_name = [element1,element2,...]</p><p>Lists are always defined with the <strong>square brackets []</strong> and the elements are separated by <strong>comma (,)</strong>.&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(317, 'List Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some of the basic operations of the list.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list&nbsp;<br>lst1 = [123, &#x27;spam&#x27;, 1.23]</p><p>print(lst1)</p><p>#---------------------<br>lst2 = [&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python is Easy&#x27; , 2014]</p><p>print(lst2)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Another way of defining list using keyword &#x27;list()&#x27;<br>lst3 &nbsp;= list([1,2,35,6,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;])</p><p>print(lst3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Joining two lists<br>lst4 = lst1 + lst2 + lst3</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetion of elements<br>lst4 = lst1*4</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty list<br>lst_empty = []</p><p>print(lst_empty)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#converting a string into a list<br>str1 = &#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;</p><p>lst = list(str1)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a list&nbsp;<br>lst1 = [123, &#x27;spam&#x27;, 1.23]</p><p>print(lst1)</p><p>#---------------------<br>lst2 = [&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python is Easy&#x27; , 2014]</p><p>print(lst2)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Another way of defining list using keyword &#x27;list()&#x27;<br>lst3 &nbsp;= list([1,2,35,6,&#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;])</p><p>print(lst3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Joining two lists<br>lst4 = lst1 + lst2 + lst3</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetion of elements<br>lst4 = lst1*4</p><p>print(lst4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty list<br>lst_empty = []</p><p>print(lst_empty)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#converting a string into a list<br>str1 = &#x27;Glowworm Academy&#x27;</p><p>lst = list(str1)</p><p>print(lst)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(318, 'List Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some of the basic operations of the list.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [12,3,123,12,90]</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sum of the list<br>print(sum(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the maximum value of the list<br>print(max(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the minimum value of the list<br>print(min(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = &#x27;sadasdasdgqqwd&#x27;</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = [12,3,123,12,90]</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sum of the list<br>print(sum(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the maximum value of the list<br>print(max(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the minimum value of the list<br>print(min(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst = &#x27;sadasdasdgqqwd&#x27;</p><p>#---------------------------</p><p>#Printing the sorted list<br>print(sorted(lst))</p><p>#---------------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(319, 'List Operations - III', 'Python', '<p>Many times in a long list we may be interested to check if there are any &lt;b&gt;empty elements&lt;/b&gt; in the list.</p><figure class=\\\"table\\\"><table><thead><tr><th><i>Keyword</i></th><th><i>Application</i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>any</td><td>It will return True when there is at least one empty element in the list</td></tr><tr><td>all</td><td>It will return True when there are all empty elements in the list</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#--------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[],[]]</p><p>#any keyword<br>print(any(lst))<br>#--------------------<br>lst = []</p><p>#all keyword<br>print(all(lst))<br>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#--------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[],[]]</p><p>#any keyword<br>print(any(lst))<br>#--------------------<br>lst = []</p><p>#all keyword<br>print(all(lst))<br>#--------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(320, 'List Slicing - I', 'Python', '<p>We store data to use it at a later point in time.</p><p>Let&#x27;s focus on how we can use list slicing to extract the store data.</p><p><strong>Always remember that Python starts indexing with 0.</strong></p><p>Create a <strong>5 element</strong> list of your choice name it to <strong>&#x27;lst&#x27;</strong></p><p>Then, copy the following code and run it.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#----------------------------</p><p>print(\"The the 0th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 1st element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 2nd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 3rd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the4th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the list<br>#----------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#----------------------------</p><p>print(\"The the 0th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 1st element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 2nd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the 3rd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the list</p><p>print(\"The the4th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the list<br>#----------------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(321, 'List Exercise - I', 'Python', '<p>Create a list of 15 elements named as <strong>lst</strong> using user input print the all the elements at even index positions.</p><p>Use <strong>positive indexing</strong> method.</p><p>Always remember, python <strong>starts indexing with 0.</strong></p>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Printing all even indexed elements.</p><p>print(\"The the 0th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[0])</p><p>print(\"The the 2nd element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[2])</p><p>print(\"The the 4th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[4])</p><p>print(\"The the 6th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[6])</p><p>print(\"The the 8th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[8])</p><p>print(\"The the 10th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[10])</p><p>print(\"The the 12th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[12])</p><p>print(\"The the 14th element from the list is: \")</p><p>print(lst[14])</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(322, 'List Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Basically, the nesting of list is putting a list within a list.</p><p>That allows the user to store the data in a multi-layer basis.</p><p><strong>Syntax</strong>:</p><p>list_name[index][index]...[index]</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong><br>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------<br>lst = [1,2,3,[&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]]</p><p>#Accessing the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;] within the main list</p><p>print(lst[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]</p><p>print(lst[3][2])</p><p>#-------------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(323, 'Dictionary', 'Python', '<p>Python dictionaries are something completely different.&nbsp;</p><p>They are not sequences at all, but are instead known as <strong>mappings</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Mappings</strong> are also collections of other objects. Some important points:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>They store objects by key instead of by relative position.</li><li>They don&#x27;t store the data in any particular order.</li><li>Dictionaries are mutable.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(324, 'Dictionary Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first dictionary and look at some basic operations.&nbsp;</p><p>This method is handy if you can spell out the entire dictionary ahead of time.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>dictionary_name = {&#x27;key1&#x27;:value1,&#x27;key2&#x27;:value2....}&nbsp;</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary of fruits&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the original dictionary</p><p>print(\"The original dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#Retrieving data from dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(d1[&#x27;fruit1&#x27;])&nbsp;</p><p>#Displaying the length of dictionary print(len(d1))&nbsp;</p><p>#Modifying a value in the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;fruit5&#x27;] = &#x27;Mango&#x27; print(d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Checking whether a particular element belongs to the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(&#x27;Apple&#x27; in d1)&nbsp;</p><p>#Removing a particular element from the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>del d1[&#x27;fruit3&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the updated dictionary</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary of fruits</p><p>d1 = {&#x27;fruit1&#x27;:&#x27;Orange&#x27;,&#x27;fruit2&#x27;:&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;fruit3&#x27;:&#x27;Banana&#x27;,&#x27;fruit4&#x27;:&#x27;Peach&#x27;,&#x27;fruit5&#x27;:&#x27;Watermelon&#x27;}</p><p>#Printing the original dictionary</p><p>print(\"The original dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>#Retrieving data from dictionary</p><p>print(d1[&#x27;fruit1&#x27;])</p><p>#Displaying the length of dictionary print(len(d1))</p><p>#Modifying a value in the dictionary</p><p>d1[&#x27;fruit5&#x27;] = &#x27;Mango&#x27; print(d1)</p><p>#Checking whether a particular element belongs to the dictionary</p><p>print(&#x27;Apple&#x27; in d1)</p><p>#Removing a particular element from the dictionary</p><p>del d1[&#x27;fruit3&#x27;]</p><p>#Printing the updated dictionary</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \", d1)</p><p>print(d1)</p><p>#------------------</p></blockquote>', '1');
