(325, 'Dictionary Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at a different way of defining a dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p>This is useful when you need to create the dictionary one field at a time.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty dictionary</p><p>d1 = {}</p><p>#Adding one element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;New York&#x27;</p><p>#Adding second element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City2&#x27;] = &#x27;Zurich&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding third element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City3&#x27;] = &#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Adding fourth element&nbsp;</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;London&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the dictionary&nbsp;</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \",d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty dictionary</p><p>d1 = {}</p><p>#Adding one element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;New York&#x27;</p><p>#Adding second element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City2&#x27;] = &#x27;Zurich&#x27;</p><p>#Adding third element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City3&#x27;] = &#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;</p><p>#Adding fourth element</p><p>d1[&#x27;City1&#x27;] = &#x27;London&#x27;</p><p>#Printing the dictionary</p><p>print(\"The updated dictionary is: \",d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(326, 'Dictionary Operations - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some other ways of defining a dictionary.&nbsp;</p><p>The first method below, involves less typing, but it requires all keys to be strings.&nbsp;</p><p>The second method below, is useful if you need to build up keys and values as sequences at runtime.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Using the keyword &#x27;dict()&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict(name=&#x27;Bob&#x27;, age=40,city = Baden, profession = &#x27;Engineer&#x27;)&nbsp;</p><p>#dict key/value tuples form&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict([(&#x27;name&#x27;,&#x27;Bob&#x27;), (&#x27;age&#x27;,40),(&#x27;city&#x27;,&#x27;Baden&#x27;), (&#x27;profession&#x27;,&#x27;Engineer&#x27;)])</p><p>&nbsp;#More on the tuples later</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong>&nbsp;</h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Using the keyword &#x27;dict()&#x27;&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict(name=&#x27;Bob&#x27;, age=40,city = Baden, profession = &#x27;Engineer&#x27;)&nbsp;</p><p>#dict key/value tuples form&nbsp;</p><p>d1 = dict([(&#x27;name&#x27;,&#x27;Bob&#x27;), (&#x27;age&#x27;,40),(&#x27;city&#x27;,&#x27;Baden&#x27;), (&#x27;profession&#x27;,&#x27;Engineer&#x27;)])</p><p>&nbsp;#More on the tuples later</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(327, 'Dictionary Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Just like the list nesting there <strong>the dictionary</strong> offers<br>the nesting functionality.</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at an example.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(328, 'Dictionary Nesting - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at how to retrieve the stored data.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>dictionary_name[&#x27;key1&#x27;][&#x27;key2&#x27;]</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>#Printing the nested dictionary<br>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#Extracting an element of the dicitonary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict1&#x27;][&#x27;city&#x27;])</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;lst&#x27; : [1,2,3,4], &#x27;lst2&#x27;: [&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d2 = {&#x27;city&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;],&#x27;Seasons&#x27;:[&#x27;Summer&#x27;,&#x27;Winter&#x27;,&#x27;Monsoon&#x27;]}</p><p>#Defining a nested dictionary<br>nested_dict = {&#x27;dict1&#x27;:d1,&#x27;dict2&#x27;:d2}</p><p>#Printing the nested dictionary<br>print(nested_dict)</p><p>#Extracting an element of the dicitonary<br>print(nested_dict[&#x27;dict1&#x27;][&#x27;city&#x27;])</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(329, 'Set', 'Python', '<p>Python <strong>Set</strong> data type is a unique way of data is stored.</p><p><strong>Some important points:</strong></p><p>1. They store objects neither by <strong>index</strong> nor using a <strong>key</strong>.<br>2. They don&#x27;t store the data in any particular order.<br>3. Sets are <strong>immutable.</strong><br>4. They only allow <strong>unique values</strong>.<br>5. Since, there is no index or key involved there is no direct&nbsp;<br>way of accessing the data stored in a set.<br><br>Though, there are ways of accessing the data from the set which will be<br>discussed in the later part of the course.</p><p>It is used in a Python program where the programmer would want the values&nbsp;<br>stored in the set to be unchanged and/or avoid duplicate values.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(330, 'Set Operations', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first set and look at few basic operations.</p><p>They are defined using <strong>curly brackets {}</strong>.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>set_name = {element1,element2,element3...}</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a set using {}<br>set1 = {1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a set using set keyword<br>set2 = set([&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7])</p><p>print(set2)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Only unique values are allowed<br>set3 = {1,2,2,2,2,234,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>set4 = {&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1}</p><p>#This will cause an error&nbsp;<br>print(set4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty set<br>set_empty = set({})</p><p>print(set_empty)</p><p>#---------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a set using {}<br>set1 = {1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set1)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a set using set keyword<br>set2 = set([&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7])</p><p>print(set2)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Only unique values are allowed<br>set3 = {1,2,2,2,2,234,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;}</p><p>print(set3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>set4 = {&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1}</p><p>#This will cause an error&nbsp;<br>print(set4)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty set<br>set_empty = set({})</p><p>print(set_empty)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(331, 'Set Exercises - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Define a list named <strong>lst1 </strong>containing <strong>5 fruits</strong> containing &nbsp;<strong>Orange, Apple, Banana, Mango, Watermelon</strong>.</li><li>Define a list named <strong>lst2</strong> containing <strong>5 vegetables</strong> containing <strong>Cucumber, Tomato, Onion, Carrot, Okra</strong>.</li><li>Define a set named <strong>set1</strong> and <strong>set2</strong></li><li>Define a set named <strong>set3</strong> by adding <strong>lst1</strong> and<strong> lst2</strong> and converting it into <strong>set</strong>.</li><li>Print all the <strong>sets</strong>.</li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', ' Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining a lst1</p><p>lst1 = [\"Orange\", \"Apple\", \"Banana\", \"Mango\", \"Watermelon\"]</p><p>print(\"The set1 is: \",set1)</p><p>#Defining a lst2</p><p>lst2 = [\"Cucumber\", \"Tomato\", \"Onion\", \"Carrot\", \"Okra\"]</p><p>print(\"The set2 is: \",set2)</p><p>#Defining a lst3</p><p>lst3 = lst1 + lst2</p><p>#Converting a list into set</p><p>set3 = set(lst3)</p><p>print(\"The new set is: \",set3)</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(332, 'Tuple', 'Python', '<p>The tuple object is similar to a list, that cannot be changed.</p><p><strong>Some important points:</strong></p><p>1. They store objects by <strong>index</strong> and <strong>relative position</strong>.<br>2. Sets are <strong>immutable.</strong><br>3. Tuples are <strong>ordered collections</strong> of <strong>arbitrary objects</strong>.<br>4. They are <strong>heterogeneous</strong> and can store all types of objects.</p><p>It is used in a Python program where the programmer would want the values&nbsp;<br>stored in the tuple to be unchanged.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(333, 'Tuple Operations - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s define your first tuple and look at few basic operations.</p><p>They are defined using <strong>round brackets ()</strong>.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>tuple_name = (element1,element2,element3...)</p><p>Let&#x27;s look at some examples</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)</p><p>#---------------------<br><br>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>print(tuple2)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>tuple4 = (&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty set<br>tuple_empty = tuple()</p><p>print(tuple_empty)<br>#---------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)</p><p>#---------------------<br><br>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>print(tuple2)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a list<br>lst &nbsp;= [1,2,3,4,5]</p><p>#Defining a dictionary<br>d1 = {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</p><p>#Defining a set with a list and dictionary&nbsp;<br>tuple4 = (&#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;, &#x27;Python&#x27;,lst, lst, lst,d1,d1,d1)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining an empty set<br>tuple_empty = tuple()</p><p>print(tuple_empty)<br>#---------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(334, 'Tuple Operations - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s look at some more tuple operations.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using &#x27;+&#x27; operator<br>tuple3 = tuple1 + tuple2</p><p>print(tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetition of elements<br>tuple3 = tuple1 * 5</p><p>print(tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------<br>#Checking whether an element belongs to a tuple<br>print(&#x27;Python&#x27; in tuple3)</p><p>print(&#x27;Russia&#x27; in tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using ()<br>tuple1 = (1,2,34,&#x27;Python&#x27;,&#x27;Glowworm&#x27;,&#x27;Academy&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1)<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using tuple keyword<br>tuple2 = tuple((1,2,3,&#x27;Apple&#x27;,&#x27;Banana&#x27;,1,2,34,7))</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Defining a tuple using &#x27;+&#x27; operator<br>tuple3 = tuple1 + tuple2</p><p>print(tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Repetition of elements<br>tuple3 = tuple1 * 5</p><p>print(tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------<br>#Checking whether an element belongs to a tuple<br>print(&#x27;Python&#x27; in tuple3)</p><p>print(&#x27;Russia&#x27; in tuple3)</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(335, 'Tuple Slicing - I', 'Python', '<p>We store data to use it at a later point in time.</p><p>Let&#x27;s focus on how we can use tuple slicing to extract the store data.</p><p><strong>Always remember that Python starts indexing with 0.</strong></p><p>Create a <strong>5 element</strong> tuple of your choice name it to <strong>&#x27;tuple1&#x27;</strong></p><p>Then, copy the following code and run it.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong><br>#---------------------</p><p>print(tuple1[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the tuple</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>print(tuple1[0]) #Prints the 0th element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[1]) #Prints the 1st element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[2]) #Prints the 2nd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3]) #Prints the 3rd element from the tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[4]) #Prints the 4th element from the tuple</p><p>#---------------------&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(336, 'Tuple Nesting - I', 'Python', '<p>Basically, the nesting of tuple is putting a tuple within a tuple.</p><p>That allows the user to store the data in a multi-layer basis.</p><p><strong>Syntax</strong>:</p><p>tuple_name[index][index]...[index]</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong></p><p>#---------------------</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;))</p><p>#Accessing the tuple (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,3,(&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;))</p><p>#Accessing the tuple (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;) within the main tuple</p><p>print(tuple1[3])</p><p>#Accessing an element within the list (&#x27;a&#x27;,&#x27;b&#x27;,&#x27;c&#x27;)</p><p>print(tuple1[3][2])</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(337, 'Tuple Nesting Exercises', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Let&#x27;s imagine you have a tuple as below:</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,(123,146,(&#x27;56$1&#x27;,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,(&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,(&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;))),211))</p><p><br>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Define the above tuple</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Orange&#x27;</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Chicago&#x27;</li><li>Write a code that prints &#x27;Python&#x27;</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-----------------------</p><p>#Defining the tuple</p><p>tuple1 = (1,2,4,&#x27;apple&#x27;,(123123,1456,(&#x27;546$21&#x27;,4590,&#x27;Orange&#x27;,(&#x27;New York&#x27;,&#x27;Chicago&#x27;,&#x27;Ahmedabad&#x27;,(&#x27;Tiger&#x27;,&#x27;Cat&#x27;,&#x27;Python&#x27;))),21321))</p><p>#Extracting the &#x27;Orange&#x27;<br>print(tuple1[4][2][2])</p><p>#Extracting the &#x27;Chicago&#x27;<br>print(tuple1[4][2][3][2])</p><p>#Extracting the &#x27;Python&#x27;<br>print(tuple1[4][2][3][4][2])</p><p>#-----------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(338, 'Statements', 'Python', '<p>So far we have learnt about Python&#x27;s built-in objects.</p><p>It&#x27;s time to learn about statements. To be more specific, conditional statements.</p><p>So, what are <strong>statements</strong> anyway?</p><p>In simple terms, statements are the things<br>you write to tell Python what your programs<br>should do.</p><p>Less informally, Python is a procedural, statement-based language.</p><p>By combining statements, you specify a procedure that Python&nbsp;<br>performs to satisfy a program’s goals.<br>&nbsp;</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(339, 'Conditional Statements', 'Python', '<p>In case a program with thousands of lines of code, it may not be required to execute the entire program<br>line by line.</p><p>It may be the case that we may only need to execute a part or some parts of the program.</p><p>Further, it may so happen that needs to be done in a particular order.</p><p>So basically, we are controlling the flow of the program (execution) based on certain needs or&nbsp;<br>less informally, conditions.</p><p>This is where we use Python&#x27;s conditional statements.</p><p>For now, we will be looking at the <strong>if</strong> statement.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.<br><br><strong>Note:</strong><br>Do notice the indentation (gap) between&nbsp;the <strong>if</strong> line and the <strong>Statements</strong> line.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(340, 'Indentation', 'Python', '<p>Before, understanding the indentation let&#x27;s look at the general structure<br>of the <strong>if</strong> statement.</p><p>We promise after this we will get into action with the <strong>if</strong> statement.</p><p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.</p><p>or looking at the more generic form</p><p>Header block:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Statement block<br>&nbsp;</p><p>What is <strong>indentation</strong> in Python?</p><p>Indentation is the gap that is provided between a <strong>Header block</strong>&nbsp;<br>and a <strong>Statement block</strong>.</p><p>Why <strong>indentation</strong> in Python?</p><p>It’s one of the main ways that Python almost forces programmers to&nbsp;<br>produce uniform, regular, and readable code.</p><p>It essentially means that you must line up your code vertically, in columns, according<br>to its logical structure.</p>', 'White (normal card)', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '1'),
(341, 'if Statement - I', 'Python', '<p><strong>Syntax:</strong></p><p>if (condition to be evaluated):<br>Statements to be executed if condition is TRUE.</p><p><strong>Some points on the indentation:</strong></p><ol><li>Technically, Python doesn’t care <strong>how you indent (tabs or spaces).</strong></li><li>Technically, Python doesn’t care <strong>how much you indent (tabs or spaces).</strong></li><li>The indentation of one nested block can be totally different from that of another.</li></ol><p>The <strong>syntax rule</strong> is only that for a given single statement block,&nbsp;all of its statements must be <strong>indented the same distance to the right</strong>.<br><br><strong>Note:</strong><br>It is advisable to select either a <strong>tab</strong> or a <strong>space</strong> as a indentation preference.</p><blockquote><p>For the entire course we are going to use a <strong>single tab</strong> as a our indentation preference.<br><br><strong>Execute the below code:</strong><br>#---------------------<br>#Defining variables<br>a = 5</p><p>b =10</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = Single Space<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp;print(a)&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = Single Tab<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(a)&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 5 Spaces<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(a)&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 5 Tabs<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(a)&nbsp;<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 1 Space and 1 tab<br>#This will give you error<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp;print(a)<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(b)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Different Indentation<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp;print(\"This is a space indented block\")</p><p>if a&gt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"This is a tab indented block\")&nbsp;</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#---------------------<br>#Defining variables<br>a = 5</p><p>b =10</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = Single Space<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(a)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = Single Tab<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(a)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 5 Spaces<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(a)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 5 Tabs<br>if a&lt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(a)&nbsp;<br>#---------------------</p><p>#Indentation = 1 Space and 1 tab<br>#This will give you error<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(a)<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(b)</p><p>#---------------------</p><p>#Different Indentation<br>if a&lt;b:<br>print(\"This is a space indented block\")</p><p>if a&gt;b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"This is a tab indented block\")</p><p>#---------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(342, 'if Statement - II', 'Python', '<p>In the process of learning about the indentation you have accomplished 2 things:</p><p>1. Mastering the syntax of if statement.<br>2. Building your first if statement.</p><p>Trust us, that <strong>if statement</strong> has much more to offer.</p><p>So let&#x27;s begin with simple <strong>if</strong> statements.</p><p>Python&#x27;s objective is to make programmers&#x27; lives simple that is why it has structures that<br>requires minimum typing.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the below code:</strong></p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#Defining variables</p><p>a = 5</p><p>b =[1,2,4,5]</p><p>c =[&#x27;Orange&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Banana&#x27;, &#x27;Papaya&#x27;]</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement<br>if a&gt;0:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"I am learning Python.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with keyword in<br>if 5 in b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"List contains a 5.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with keyword in<br>if &#x27;Papaya&#x27; in c:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"List contains a Papaya.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;==&#x27; operator<br>if a== 5:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is 5.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;!=&#x27; operator<br>if a!= 6:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is not 6.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;4:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is greater than 4.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;=&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;=0:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is greater than or equal to 0.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;7:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is less than 7.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;=&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;=100:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is greater than or equal 100.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p></blockquote>', 'White (normal card)', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------</p><p>#Defining variables</p><p>a = 5</p><p>b =[1,2,4,5]</p><p>c =[&#x27;Orange&#x27;, &#x27;Apple&#x27;, &#x27;Banana&#x27;, &#x27;Papaya&#x27;]</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement<br>if a&gt;0:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"I am learning Python.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with keyword in<br>if 5 in b:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"List contains a 5.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with keyword in<br>if &#x27;Papaya&#x27; in c:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"List contains a Papaya.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;==&#x27; operator<br>if a== 5:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is 5.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;!=&#x27; operator<br>if a!= 6:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is not 6.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;4:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is greater than 4.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&gt;=&#x27; operator<br>if a&gt;=0:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is greater than or equal to 0.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;7:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;print(\"Value of a is less than 7.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p><p>#if statement with &#x27;=&lt;&#x27; operator<br>if a&lt;=100:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"Value of a is greater than or equal 100.\")</p><p>#-------------------</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(343, 'if Statement Exercises - I', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><ol><li>Take two numbers from the user store them into <strong>num1 </strong>and <strong>num2</strong>.</li><li>Using the if..elif..else statement write a code that check following condition.<ol><li><strong>num1</strong> is greater than <strong>num2</strong></li><li><strong>num2</strong> is greater than <strong>num1</strong></li><li><strong>num1</strong> equals to <strong>num2</strong></li></ol></li><li>Print the following message for in case of either of condition is true.<ol><li><strong>num1</strong> is greater than <strong>num2</strong>.</li><li><strong>num2</strong> is greater than <strong>num1</strong>.</li><li><strong>num1</strong> equals to <strong>num2</strong>.</li></ol></li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining numbers&nbsp;</p><p>num1&nbsp; = 10</p><p>num2&nbsp; = 20</p><p>#Writing the if..elif..else statement for checking condition</p><p>if (num1&gt;num2):</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"num1 is greater than num2.)</p><p>elif(num1</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"num2 is greater than num1.\")</p><p>else:</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"num1 equals to num2.\")</p></blockquote>', '1'),
(344, 'if Statement Exercises - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s test your knowledge.</p><p>Write a code that does the following.</p><ol><li>Ask the user to enter a year of their choice.</li><li>Check whether the year is a leap year or not.</li><li>Print an appropriate message.<ul><li>This is a leap year</li><li>This is not a leap year</li></ul></li></ol>', 'White (normal card)', 'Use the knowledge gained from from previous lessons.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining year</p><p>year = 1234</p><p>#if...elif...else statement</p><p>if (year%4 == 0):</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"This is a leap year\")</p><p>else:</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(\"This is not a leap year\")</p></blockquote>', '1'),
