(1813, 'Population vs Sample', 'Python', '<p>Making decisions involve analyzing data.</p><p>For analyzing data the data needs to be collected.</p><p>The process of collecting data is called Sampling.</p><p>The collected data is called Sample.</p><p>For example, if we want to evaluate the average age of an entire country it is not practical to record everyone&#x27;s age and then evaluate the average.</p><p>It is feasible to ask few people (Sample) and use that information to estimate the average age of the entire country (Population).</p><p>Generally, the data that is collected for analysis is a subset of the larger data set.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"&amp;mple \r\nR)pulation \"></p>', '', ' Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1814, 'Population vs Sample - II', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s understand some basic terms that will be referred to time and again in this course.</p><p>1. Population - The entire data set.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;○ This contains all the data points/observations/occurrences.<br>&nbsp;○ Example: &nbsp;A to Z alphabet (26 letters)<br>2. Sample - Subset of the entire data set.<br>&nbsp;○ This contains few data points from the entire data set.<br>&nbsp;○ Example: &nbsp;Vowels (A,E,I,O,U)</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#Defining a population of numbers&nbsp;<br>population = list(range(1,10))</p><p>#Defining sample1<br>sample1 = list(range(1,4))</p><p>#Defining sample2<br>sample2 = list(range(4,8))</p><p>#Printing the population<br>print(\"The population is: \",population)</p><p>#Printing the samples<br>print(\"The sample1 is: \",sample1)</p><p>print(\"The sample2 is: \",sample2)</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p>', '', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4>Sample Code:</h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining a population of numbers&nbsp;<br>population = list(range(1,10))</p><p>#Defining sample1<br>sample1 = list(range(1,4))</p><p>#Defining sample2<br>sample2 = list(range(4,8))</p><p>#Printing the population<br>print(\"The population is: \",population)</p><p>#Printing the samples<br>print(\"The sample1 is: \",sample1)</p><p>print(\"The sample2 is: \",sample2)</p></blockquote>', '11'),
(1815, 'Variable', 'Python', '<p>Variables is any quantity that can vary.</p><p>We are familiar with the word variable from algebra by using variables like x or y which represent an unknown quantity.</p><p>However, in Statistics we deal with different types of variables</p><p>Following are the ones which we will be mainly dealing with:<br>1. Categorical Variable<br>2. Numerical Variable<br>3. Continuous Variable<br>4. Discrete Variable<br>5. Dependent Variable<br>6. Independent Variable<br>Random Variable</p>', '', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1816, 'Variable - II', 'Python', '<p><strong>Categorical variable</strong> -It is a variable that isn’t numerical.&nbsp;</p><ul><li>It describes data that fits into categories.&nbsp;</li><li><strong>Example:</strong> Eye colours (variables include: blue, green, brown, hazel)</li></ul><p>Categorical Variable has two sub categories.</p><ol><li><strong>Nominal variable</strong><ol><li>A type of categorical variable where the categories are not defined in any specific order.</li><li>&nbsp;<strong>Example:</strong> Gender (Male, Female, Other)</li></ol></li><li><strong>Ordinal variable</strong><ol><li>A type of categorical variable where the categories are in a pre-defined in specific order.</li><li><strong>Example:</strong> High school class rankings (1st, 2nd, 3rd etc.)</li></ol></li></ol>', '', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1817, 'Variable - III', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s see how categorical variables are relevant in a real life case.</p><p>Let&#x27;s create a database of employees.</p><p>Following should be noted:</p><ul><li>Categorical variables : City, Gender and Employee rating</li><li>Nominal variables: City and Gender</li><li>Ordinal variable: Employee Rating</li><li>Joe and Tom are in one category based on city (New York)</li><li>Jane and Molly are in one category based on gender (Female)</li><li>Tom and Harry are in one category based on employee rating (High)</li></ul><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>Feel free to draw identify more categories to deepen your understanding.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Name&#x27;:[&#x27;Joe&#x27;, &#x27;Jane&#x27;, &#x27;Tom&#x27;, &#x27;Harry&#x27;, &#x27;Molly&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Age&#x27;:[&#x27;29&#x27;, &#x27;39&#x27;, &#x27;21&#x27;, &#x27;30&#x27;, &#x27;40&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;City&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;, &#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Gender&#x27;:[&#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Employee Rating&#x27;: [&#x27;Low&#x27;, &#x27;Medium&#x27;, &#x27;High&#x27;, &#x27;High&#x27;, &#x27;Low&#x27;]}<br>&nbsp;<br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)<br>#-------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '', '', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Name&#x27;:[&#x27;Joe&#x27;, &#x27;Jane&#x27;, &#x27;Tom&#x27;, &#x27;Harry&#x27;, &#x27;Molly&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Age&#x27;:[&#x27;29&#x27;, &#x27;39&#x27;, &#x27;21&#x27;, &#x27;30&#x27;, &#x27;40&#x27;],<br>&#x27;City&#x27;:[&#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;, &#x27;New York&#x27;, &#x27;Mumbai&#x27;, &#x27;Baden&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Gender&#x27;:[&#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Employee Rating&#x27;: [&#x27;Low&#x27;, &#x27;Medium&#x27;, &#x27;High&#x27;, &#x27;High&#x27;, &#x27;Low&#x27;]}<br><br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)<br>#-------------------------------</p></blockquote>', '11'),
(1818, 'Variable - IV', 'Python', '<p><strong>Numerical variable</strong> -It is a variable that is numerical.&nbsp;</p><ul><li>It describes data in numbers.</li><li>Example: Age, Height, Weight</li></ul><p>Categorical Variable has two sub categories.</p><ol><li>Discrete variable<ol><li>A type of numerical variable that are countable in a finite amount of time.</li><li>Example: Change in your pocket</li></ol></li><li>Continuous variable<ol><li>A type of numerical variable that can not be counted in a finite amount of time.</li><li>Example: Age, Height, Weight</li></ol></li></ol><p><strong>Note:</strong><br>Discrete variables can take up only specific values and not any in-between values between two values.</p><p>That is to say that if a discrete variable is between 1 to 10 then it can take up finite number of values such as 1,2,3,4...10 but it can&#x27;t take up values such as 1.1, 1.1235.6.7 (in-between values).</p><p>However, continuous variables can take any value including the specific values.</p><p>That is to say that if a continuous variable has a range of values of 1 to 10 then it can take up infinite number of values &nbsp;1,2,3,4...10 &nbsp;including values such as 1.1, 1.1235.6.7 (in-between values).<br>&nbsp;</p>', '', ' Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1819, 'Variable - V', 'Python', '<p>Let&#x27;s see how numerical variables are relevant in a real life case.</p><p>Let&#x27;s create a database of employees.</p><p><strong>Following should be noted:</strong><br>• Numerical variables : Age, Employee rating and Fixed Pay<br>• Continuous variables: Age, Fixed Pay<br>• Discrete variable: Employee rating</p><p><strong>Note:</strong></p><p>Feel free to draw your own conclusions to deepen your understanding.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Name&#x27;:[&#x27;Joe&#x27;, &#x27;Jane&#x27;, &#x27;Tom&#x27;, &#x27;Harry&#x27;, &#x27;Molly&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Age&#x27;:[&#x27;29&#x27;, &#x27;39&#x27;, &#x27;21&#x27;, &#x27;30&#x27;, &#x27;40&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Employee rating out of 10&#x27;:[&#x27;3.5&#x27;, &#x27;5&#x27;, &#x27;10&#x27;, &#x27;8.5&#x27;, &#x27;7.5&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Gender&#x27;:[&#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Fixed Pay&#x27;: [10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 100000]}<br>&nbsp;<br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>', '', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Name&#x27;:[&#x27;Joe&#x27;, &#x27;Jane&#x27;, &#x27;Tom&#x27;, &#x27;Harry&#x27;, &#x27;Molly&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Age&#x27;:[&#x27;29&#x27;, &#x27;39&#x27;, &#x27;21&#x27;, &#x27;30&#x27;, &#x27;40&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Employee rating out of 10&#x27;:[&#x27;3.5&#x27;, &#x27;5&#x27;, &#x27;10&#x27;, &#x27;8.5&#x27;, &#x27;7.5&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Gender&#x27;:[&#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Male&#x27;, &#x27;Female&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Fixed Pay&#x27;: [10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 100000]}<br><br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p></blockquote>', '11'),
(1820, 'Variable - VI', 'Python', '<p>In many cases, continuous variables can be made into discrete variable.</p><p>For example age can be considered a continuous variable age can take up infinite amount of time to count.</p><p>Wondering how so?</p><p>For example a person&#x27;s Age can technically be recorded as 25 years, 10 months, 2 days, 5 hours, 4 seconds, 4 milliseconds, 8 nanoseconds, 99 picoseconds.. and so on.</p><p>This makes the age a continuous variable but in real life scenarios it is not practical to record or store age in this manner.</p><p>We prefer the age to be recorded just only in years &nbsp;so in case of above example the age will be recorded or stored as&nbsp;<br>25 years.</p><p>It is important to note that in many practical cases in data analytics and data science scenarios continuous variables are treated as discrete variables for the ease of calculation.<br>&nbsp;</p>', '', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1821, 'Variable - VII', 'Python', '<p>Another type of variable is also quite important in terms of statistical analysis and prediction.</p><p><strong>Following are the variable types:</strong></p><ol><li>Independent variable<ol><li>Also known as the <strong>predictor variable</strong>.</li></ol></li><li>&nbsp;Dependent variable<ol><li>Also known as the <strong>predicted variable</strong>.</li></ol></li></ol><p>For example, if you are trying to predict the property prices in a particular area.</p><p><strong>The price of a property will be influenced by following factors:</strong></p><ol><li>Area&nbsp;</li><li>Number of rooms</li><li>Type of the property</li></ol><p>Here the dependent variable is Price.</p><p>Here the independent variables are Area, Number of rooms and Type of property.</p><p>Using the independent variables the value of dependent variable is predicted.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Execute the code below:</strong></p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Area (sq.ft)&#x27;:[200, 240, 500, 400, 1000],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Number of rooms&#x27;:[2, 5, 1, 3, 4],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Type of property&#x27;:[&#x27;Independent house&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Studio apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;],<br>&nbsp;&#x27;Price&#x27;:[10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 100000]}<br>&nbsp;<br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '', 'Execute the code and observe the output.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#Importing necessary libraries<br>#Do not change this<br>import micropip<br>micropip.install(&#x27;pandas&#x27;)</p><p>#-------------------------------<br>import pandas as pd</p><p>database = {&#x27;Area (sq.ft)&#x27;:[200, 240, 500, 400, 1000],<br>&#x27;Number of rooms&#x27;:[2, 5, 1, 3, 4],<br>&#x27;Type of property&#x27;:[&#x27;Independent house&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Studio apartment&#x27;, &#x27;Apartment&#x27;],<br>&#x27;Price&#x27;:[10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 100000]}<br><br>#Converting into data frame<br>database = pd.DataFrame(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p><p>#printing the database</p><p>print(database)</p><p>#-------------------------------</p></blockquote>', '11'),
(1822, 'Randomisation in Statistics', 'Python', '<p>What is a Statistical experiment?</p><p>A statistical experiment is the procedure of drawing a sample with the intention of making a decision.</p><p>Experiments are carried out to investigate the cause and effect relationship between two variables.</p><p>A statistical experiment can be as simple as a coin toss to as complex as studying the effectiveness of a newly invented drug.</p><p>What is a random statistical experiment?</p><p>A statistical experiment which has a random outcome.</p><p>For example: rolling a die, choosing a card, choosing a bingo ball etc.</p><p>What is Randomization?</p><p>Randomization in a statistical experiment is where you choose your sample randomly.</p><p>Why Randomization is important?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Let&#x27;s say you are studying the outcome of a coin toss.</p><p>A fair coin would have 50-50 probability of getting heads and tails after each toss.</p><p>Let&#x27;s say you select a coin which is not fair (it gives more heads).</p><p>Now, if you toss the coin 10 times in case of an unfair coin it will give more heads then tails.</p><p>This makes the experiment outcome is not random but rather biased(getting one outcome more than the other).</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '', 'Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '', '11'),
(1823, 'Python interview question - I', 'Python', '<p><strong>What is the difference between a list and a tuple?</strong></p>', '', 'Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<p><strong>What is the difference between a list and a tuple?</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i><strong>List</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Tuple</strong></i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>List is immutable object in Python.</td><td>List is mutable object in Python.</td></tr><tr><td>Consumes more memory.</td><td>Consumes less memory.</td></tr><tr><td>List is stored in two blocks of memory.</td><td>Tuple is stored in a single block of memory.</td></tr><tr><td>Lists are defined with square brackets [].</td><td>Lists are defined with circular brackets ().</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '13'),
(1827, 'Python Interview question - 2', 'Python', '<p><strong>Write a code that defines a list and convert it into a tuple and a set.</strong></p>', '', ' Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Define a list&nbsp;</p><p>lst = [1,2,3,4]</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>#Converting list into tuple</p><p>tuple1 = tuple(lst)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>#Converting list into set</p><p>set1 = set(lst)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the list</p><p>print(\"The list is: \",lst)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the tuple</p><p>print(\"The tuple is: \",tuple1)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>#Printing the set</p><p>print(\"The set is: \",set1)</p></blockquote>', '13'),
(1828, 'Python Interview question - 3', 'Python', '<p>Write a code that produces the following pattern</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>*******</p><p>******</p><p>*****</p><p>****</p><p>***</p><p>**</p><p>*</p>', '', 'Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>for i in range(7):</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; print(&#x27;*&#x27;*(7-i))</p></blockquote>', '13'),
(1829, 'Python Interview question - 4', 'Python', '<p><strong>What is a data frame?</strong></p><p><strong>Name the package that is used to perform data analysis in Python using data frame.</strong></p>', '', 'Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<p><strong>What is a data frame?</strong></p><ul><li>DataFrame is a 2-dimensional labeled data structure with columns of potentially different types. You can think of it like a spreadsheet.</li></ul><p><strong>Name the package that is used to perform data analysis in Python using data frame.</strong></p><ul><li>That is Pandas. Pandas is a fast, powerful, flexible and easy to use open source data analysis and manipulation tool, built on top of the Python programming language.</li></ul>', '13'),
(1830, 'Python Interview question - 5', 'Python', '<p><strong>What is the difference between a set and a dictionary?</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '', ' Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<p><strong>What is the difference between a set and a dictionary?</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i><strong>Dictionary</strong></i></th><th><i><strong>Set</strong></i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A dictionary is an <i>unordered</i> collection of data that stores data in key-value pairs.</td><td>A set is an <i>unordered</i> collection.</td></tr><tr><td>Dictionary does not allow duplicate keys but the values can be duplicated.</td><td>Sets do not allow duplicate values</td></tr><tr><td>Example d1= {&#x27;a&#x27;:1,&#x27;b&#x27;:2,&#x27;c&#x27;:3}</td><td>Example set1 = {1,2,3}</td></tr><tr><td>Dictionary has a method <strong>.sort()</strong> to sort the elements inside it.</td><td>Set elements can not be ordered</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', '13'),
(1831, 'Python Interview question - 6', 'Python', '<ol><li><strong>Difference between array and list?</strong></li><li><strong>When list is used and when array is used?</strong></li></ol>', '', ' Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<p><strong>Difference between array and list?</strong></p><figure class=\"table\"><table><thead><tr><th><i>List</i></th><th><i>Array</i></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Can consist of elements belonging to different data types</td><td>Only consists of elements belonging to the same data type</td></tr><tr><td>Greater flexibility allows easy modification (addition, deletion) of data</td><td>Less flexibility since addition, deletion has to be done element wise</td></tr><tr><td>No need to explicitly import a module for declaration</td><td>Need to explicitly import a module for declaration</td></tr><tr><td>Cannot directly handle arithmetic operations</td><td>Can directly handle arithmetic operations</td></tr><tr><td>The entire list can be printed without any explicit looping</td><td>A loop has to be formed to print or access the components of array</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>When list is used and when array is used?</strong></p><ul><li>List is used when user wants to store <strong>multiple data type based elements</strong> in one variable.</li><li>Array is used when user wants to store <strong>only single data types based elements</strong>&nbsp;in one variable.</li></ul>', '13'),
(1832, 'Python Interview question - 7', 'Python', '<p><strong>Write a code that does the following.</strong></p><ol><li>Define a string&nbsp;</li><li>Converting it into list</li><li>Reverse the list</li></ol>', '', ' Click on the Reveal answer.  Click on the Submit and then next to go to the next lesson.', '<blockquote><h4><strong>Sample Code:</strong></h4></blockquote><blockquote><p>#Defining a string</p><p>string1&nbsp; = \"I am learning Python\"</p><p>#Defining a string</p><p>lst&nbsp; = list(string1)</p><p>#Defining a string</p><p>lst1 = lst.reverse()</p><p>#Print the reversed list</p><p>print(\"The reversed list is: \",lst1)</p></blockquote>', '13');
